00:00:47.710 --> 00:00:51.570
The focus of our panel today is
on the millions of Americans,

00:00:51.570 --> 00:00:55.520
both children and adults,
who struggle with reading.

00:00:55.520 --> 00:00:58.760
The Washington Post ran an
article on November 1st,

00:00:58.760 --> 00:01:03.930
2016 that was entitled
"Hiding in plain sight:

00:01:03.930 --> 00:01:06.420
The adult literacy crisis."

00:01:06.420 --> 00:01:10.130
Trouble with reading truly
is a hidden disability.

00:01:10.130 --> 00:01:13.810
The majority of people in this
category have no outward signs

00:01:13.810 --> 00:01:17.700
of a problem, and they're
typically quite intelligent.

00:01:17.700 --> 00:01:21.450
They're also highly
motivated to keep others

00:01:21.450 --> 00:01:23.460
from knowing that
they can't read.

00:01:23.460 --> 00:01:27.320
Somebody on an earlier panel
mentioned the same associated

00:01:27.320 --> 00:01:30.030
with being a struggling reader
and that's a huge issue,

00:01:30.030 --> 00:01:32.000
the shame and embarrassment.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:36.160
So this is not something that
they share freely with friends,

00:01:36.160 --> 00:01:41.260
with co-workers, with educators,
with their health providers,

00:01:41.260 --> 00:01:44.590
and their own family may not
even recognize the extent

00:01:44.590 --> 00:01:46.260
of the problem.

00:01:46.260 --> 00:01:50.180
So many people in the public
at large simply aren't aware

00:01:50.180 --> 00:01:52.470
that a problem this big exists.

00:01:52.470 --> 00:01:55.670
Our panel today is going to
share some insights on Americans

00:01:55.670 --> 00:01:58.750
who struggle with reading
for a variety of reasons

00:01:58.750 --> 00:02:01.640
and also talk-- will talk
about the types of programs

00:02:01.640 --> 00:02:04.760
and technology that can
help them gain access

00:02:04.760 --> 00:02:06.130
to printed materials.

00:02:06.130 --> 00:02:10.400
So I have a couple of slides
just with some basic statistics

00:02:10.400 --> 00:02:13.760
on the scope and impact of
reading struggles for children

00:02:13.760 --> 00:02:16.010
and for adults in
the United States.

00:02:16.010 --> 00:02:18.400
The first two slides
are an infographic

00:02:18.400 --> 00:02:21.000
from the National Center
on Learning Disabilities.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:23.210
We're not going to go
through all the statistics,

00:02:23.210 --> 00:02:27.040
but basically one in five
American children struggles

00:02:27.040 --> 00:02:29.810
with a significant learning
or attention challenge,

00:02:29.810 --> 00:02:35.110
and the vast majority of them
do struggle with reading.

00:02:35.110 --> 00:02:37.940
Learning to read is a
challenging task for the brain.

00:02:37.940 --> 00:02:39.890
So we shouldn't really
be surprise

00:02:39.890 --> 00:02:42.250
that so many people
struggle with it,

00:02:42.250 --> 00:02:44.860
but nonetheless this
is a problem which--

00:02:44.860 --> 00:02:46.160
with which nationally,

00:02:46.160 --> 00:02:49.510
we're really honestly not
making very good progress.

00:02:49.510 --> 00:02:52.870
And it's important to understand
that the majority of children

00:02:52.870 --> 00:02:55.850
who struggle with reading
unfortunately today grow

00:02:55.850 --> 00:02:59.900
into adults who are still
struggling with reading.

00:02:59.900 --> 00:03:02.290
And let's see.

00:03:02.290 --> 00:03:07.950
This is-- this slide
is from ProLiteracy,

00:03:07.950 --> 00:03:10.790
the adult literacy
education organization.

00:03:10.790 --> 00:03:12.620
They do fantastic work.

00:03:12.620 --> 00:03:15.920
Proliteracy.org is
their website.

00:03:15.920 --> 00:03:19.410
And you can see here
about 36 million adults

00:03:19.410 --> 00:03:23.400
in the United States cannot
read at a third grade level.

00:03:23.400 --> 00:03:26.640
But it's estimated that
up to 50% of adults

00:03:26.640 --> 00:03:29.790
in the United States cannot read
and comprehend a book written

00:03:29.790 --> 00:03:31.130
at the eight grade level.

00:03:31.130 --> 00:03:34.580
Fifty percent, I mean
that's a lot of people.

00:03:34.580 --> 00:03:38.260
And we know that
children of parents

00:03:38.260 --> 00:03:41.340
who are poor readers
have a higher probability

00:03:41.340 --> 00:03:43.090
of being a poor reader
themselves.

00:03:43.090 --> 00:03:44.830
There's the genetic component.

00:03:44.830 --> 00:03:48.570
Dyslexia for example is
very strongly inherited.

00:03:48.570 --> 00:03:52.370
If an adult has dyslexia, each
of their children has a 30

00:03:52.370 --> 00:03:55.160
to 50% chance of
having dyslexia.

00:03:55.160 --> 00:03:57.780
But then if you're
an adult poor reader,

00:03:57.780 --> 00:04:00.690
you're probably not going to
surround yourself with books

00:04:00.690 --> 00:04:03.080
and other printed
materials in your home.

00:04:03.080 --> 00:04:06.160
You're probably not going to
model reading for pleasure

00:04:06.160 --> 00:04:08.300
or information for
your children.

00:04:08.300 --> 00:04:09.600
And you're probably not going

00:04:09.600 --> 00:04:11.760
to read very many books
with your children.

00:04:11.760 --> 00:04:16.600
And so, this is a major
intergenerational challenge.

