What do you--

00:08:40.560 --> 00:08:41.860
&gt;&gt; Laura Bailet: Yes,
that's the remote,

00:08:41.860 --> 00:08:43.160
so the green will advance.

00:08:43.160 --> 00:08:44.460
&gt;&gt; Elsa Cardenas-Hagan:
Thank you.

00:08:44.460 --> 00:08:46.250
Good afternoon and thank you for
sticking with us this afternoon.

00:08:46.250 --> 00:08:50.510
I'm Elsa Cardenas-Hagan and
I am an English learner.

00:08:50.510 --> 00:08:54.150
So I understand the
experience of an English learner

00:08:54.150 --> 00:08:56.990
and during my time was when
there was no such thing

00:08:56.990 --> 00:08:59.680
as bilingual education
and where we were punished

00:08:59.680 --> 00:09:02.810
if we used our native
language in the school ground

00:09:02.810 --> 00:09:04.630
and in the lunch room.

00:09:04.630 --> 00:09:07.710
And so, you know, as a
young girl, being terrified

00:09:07.710 --> 00:09:11.600
to speak your home language
and then not realizing

00:09:11.600 --> 00:09:13.990
that your home language is
such a beautiful language

00:09:13.990 --> 00:09:16.790
and such a beautiful
thing and I didn't realize

00:09:16.790 --> 00:09:19.720
that until middle school
because in middle school,

00:09:19.720 --> 00:09:22.680
that is when you take
foreign language.

00:09:22.680 --> 00:09:26.520
And all of a sudden, I
could shine as they look

00:09:26.520 --> 00:09:30.560
at what I know and look
at my culture and look

00:09:30.560 --> 00:09:31.860
at the things that I know.

00:09:31.860 --> 00:09:35.580
But it was like, OK, hide
who you in these early years

00:09:35.580 --> 00:09:39.920
but now no, we will
not hide who we are.

00:09:39.920 --> 00:09:44.300
And so a beautiful thing is
that we now have available

00:09:44.300 --> 00:09:46.310
to children-- you
know, when I heard

00:09:46.310 --> 00:09:49.020
that somebody is saying
I'm an ESL specialist,

00:09:49.020 --> 00:09:52.290
English as a second language
specialist, and that's great

00:09:52.290 --> 00:09:56.460
because there's less than 3% of
them in our whole United States,

00:09:56.460 --> 00:10:00.150
less than 3% and yet we're
the fastest growing population

00:10:00.150 --> 00:10:02.110
in our schools.

00:10:02.110 --> 00:10:05.260
And so, you know,
we talk about--

00:10:05.260 --> 00:10:06.810
you know, we want
to be prepared.

00:10:06.810 --> 00:10:08.950
We want to reach these students.

00:10:08.950 --> 00:10:13.110
We want to reach, you know, all
our African-American population.

00:10:13.110 --> 00:10:15.970
We want to know about the
culture and the language

00:10:15.970 --> 00:10:18.930
so that they will want
to be responsive to us,

00:10:18.930 --> 00:10:21.200
so that they will
want to be engaged

00:10:21.200 --> 00:10:24.620
and enthusiastic about learning.

00:10:24.620 --> 00:10:28.010
And I hope Benita is still
here because I have my little--

00:10:28.010 --> 00:10:33.400
there she is, my own
dedication to Barbara Bush.

00:10:33.400 --> 00:10:36.660
And unfortunately
Benita accepted this

00:10:36.660 --> 00:10:40.570
but I was giving a speech in
Houston and talking about all

00:10:40.570 --> 00:10:43.730
of our reading reform efforts
and about how, you know,

00:10:43.730 --> 00:10:45.920
I lived in one of the
poorest communities

00:10:45.920 --> 00:10:51.000
of the whole United States
for a middle size city.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:53.680
And despite that, through
our efforts, you know,

00:10:53.680 --> 00:10:56.700
we've been able to-- and
we know it's a 100% frame

00:10:56.700 --> 00:10:58.000
reduced length.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:10:59.300
We feed them breakfast
and lunch and we have

00:10:59.300 --> 00:11:03.260
after school programs that,
you know, also give dinner.

00:11:03.260 --> 00:11:06.410
But we keep them there, you
know, to do the extra things,

00:11:06.410 --> 00:11:11.060
you know, the arts and the
music and the books and reading.

00:11:11.060 --> 00:11:14.660
But one of the things when I
gave a speech, I had so wanted

00:11:14.660 --> 00:11:16.050
to meet Mrs. Barbara Bush.

00:11:16.050 --> 00:11:19.280
And I was in Houston and
I didn't get to meet her

00:11:19.280 --> 00:11:22.130
because there was like a
thousand people that day

00:11:22.130 --> 00:11:24.330
and she was there
in the audience.

00:11:24.330 --> 00:11:28.130
And so I went back to my own
community and I thought oh,

00:11:28.130 --> 00:11:29.840
I missed the chance
to, you know,

00:11:29.840 --> 00:11:31.860
at least great a
former first lady.

00:11:31.860 --> 00:11:33.510
How cool would that be?

00:11:33.510 --> 00:11:36.620
Well, I get a phone call
at my office and says,

00:11:36.620 --> 00:11:38.990
it's Mrs. Barbara
Bush on the line.

00:11:38.990 --> 00:11:41.340
And I was like, hello,
is that you Juanito,

00:11:41.340 --> 00:11:42.900
playing a joke on me, you know.

00:11:42.900 --> 00:11:45.080
Because I talked
about how I didn't get

00:11:45.080 --> 00:11:47.140
to meet the first lady.

00:11:47.140 --> 00:11:49.530
They go, no, for real,
this is Mrs. Bush.

00:11:49.530 --> 00:11:55.600
And then she says, you go girl,
you blew me away and I'm going

00:11:55.600 --> 00:11:59.420
to have you come to my
celebration of reading

00:11:59.420 --> 00:12:02.440
in Houston, and you're going to
tell about the works that you do

00:12:02.440 --> 00:12:04.700
and you're going
to write a speech.

00:12:04.700 --> 00:12:07.400
And I'm like, Mrs. Bush,
I don't write speeches.

00:12:07.400 --> 00:12:11.220
I just-- I'm a storyteller
and I tell the story of what--

00:12:11.220 --> 00:12:12.520
you know, the work that we do.

00:12:12.520 --> 00:12:14.300
She was, no, you're going
to write your speech.

00:12:14.300 --> 00:12:16.180
So I'm like, yes, ma'am.

00:12:16.180 --> 00:12:17.680
So I wrote that speech.

00:12:17.680 --> 00:12:19.800
I'm like, who are the
other speakers by the way?

00:12:19.800 --> 00:12:24.550
She goes, oh, you know,
H. W. and George W.

00:12:24.550 --> 00:12:27.750
and [inaudible] all
this, Mrs. Baker.

00:12:27.750 --> 00:12:30.230
And I was like, oh my God.

00:12:30.230 --> 00:12:32.410
So I write the speech
and I send it to her.

00:12:32.410 --> 00:12:34.280
And she calls me back
and she goes, well,

00:12:34.280 --> 00:12:37.130
let's talk a little bit
more about your speech.

00:12:37.130 --> 00:12:38.430
I'm like, yes ma'am.

00:12:38.430 --> 00:12:40.110
And she goes, you know,
you mentioned George W.,

00:12:40.110 --> 00:12:41.890
don't mention him, you know.

00:12:41.890 --> 00:12:44.310
And she goes, this is
nothing about the Bush's.

00:12:44.310 --> 00:12:48.040
It's about what you did in your
local community and nothing

00:12:48.040 --> 00:12:51.010
about the governor of our
state and how he helped you.

00:12:51.010 --> 00:12:52.490
And I'm like, yes ma'am.

00:12:52.490 --> 00:12:54.660
And I said, well, while
I got you on the line,

00:12:54.660 --> 00:12:56.820
I need a little bit more
money and I know you're going

00:12:56.820 --> 00:12:59.710
to raise millions of dollars
that evening, so do you mind

00:12:59.710 --> 00:13:03.610
if I talk about children
also with dyslexia

00:13:03.610 --> 00:13:07.420
and I would have a dream that in
one of the poorest communities

00:13:07.420 --> 00:13:11.870
that we would have an expert on
every campus in our city to work

00:13:11.870 --> 00:13:15.310
with these children who are
English learners, who, you know,

00:13:15.310 --> 00:13:18.370
have these disabilities, you
know, these hidden disabilities

00:13:18.370 --> 00:13:20.660
that no one knows and
we just weave around.

00:13:20.660 --> 00:13:23.420
And she goes, well, how
much are you needing, right?

00:13:23.420 --> 00:13:25.850
And so I tell her the
amount and she says,

00:13:25.850 --> 00:13:28.850
you may put that
in there, you know.

00:13:28.850 --> 00:13:30.150
And I'm like, OK.

00:13:30.150 --> 00:13:31.450
So that evening, I get there

