00:14:38.530 --> 00:14:40.810
all people that they
would be literacy--

00:14:40.810 --> 00:14:43.500
and that they would achieve
literacy because she had

00:14:43.500 --> 00:14:44.810
such a love of literacy.

00:14:44.810 --> 00:14:47.070
And also I had personal
experience with, you know,

00:14:47.070 --> 00:14:49.720
a child who had difficulty
in these--

00:14:49.720 --> 00:14:52.430
those early years with literacy.

00:14:52.430 --> 00:14:55.960
And so I'm here today to talk
to you about these children,

00:14:55.960 --> 00:14:58.030
about what Laura
here is telling you

00:14:58.030 --> 00:15:01.730
about that hidden
disability, that being dyslexia

00:15:01.730 --> 00:15:04.350
and what goes around, and
I am the Vice President

00:15:04.350 --> 00:15:07.320
of the International
Dyslexia Association.

00:15:07.320 --> 00:15:11.240
And so, we are on a mission to
really promote what we want,

00:15:11.240 --> 00:15:15.820
a term to be used today
called structured literacy.

00:15:15.820 --> 00:15:19.410
And that's a term that
we want to really promote

00:15:19.410 --> 00:15:23.560
as here we have these
students who were so bright,

00:15:23.560 --> 00:15:27.310
so intelligent, nothing
to do with intelligence

00:15:27.310 --> 00:15:30.220
but they struggle
with these, you know,

00:15:30.220 --> 00:15:34.840
skills of how do you read,
how does reading work.

00:15:34.840 --> 00:15:39.250
And as we look at this and as
we see in this, Laura mentioned

00:15:39.250 --> 00:15:41.140
to you the majority of children

00:15:41.140 --> 00:15:43.550
in special education
services are there

00:15:43.550 --> 00:15:48.010
because of a reading disability,
and we will tell you 15 to 20%

00:15:48.010 --> 00:15:50.380
of those kids have dyslexia.

00:15:50.380 --> 00:15:54.370
And as we look at this, we see,
what are the issues with them?

00:15:54.370 --> 00:15:57.360
So, one of the primary issues
is that they have trouble just

00:15:57.360 --> 00:16:01.470
with the simple things of being
able to process those sounds.

00:16:01.470 --> 00:16:04.450
And, you know, I'm a Spanish
speaker so we don't have

00:16:04.450 --> 00:16:07.600
as many sounds in our language
as you do in yours, you know.

00:16:07.600 --> 00:16:09.990
Some will say 44 to
46 sounds and we have

00:16:09.990 --> 00:16:12.580
about half of that many sounds.

00:16:12.580 --> 00:16:15.550
And so, just that ability
to process those sounds.

00:16:15.550 --> 00:16:18.550
And, you know, a lot of research
into exactly where that is

00:16:18.550 --> 00:16:22.090
in the brain, Heschl's gyrus,
the left angular gyrus.

00:16:22.090 --> 00:16:24.510
And if you don't have that,
then how are you going

00:16:24.510 --> 00:16:26.580
to put those letters
and sounds together

00:16:26.580 --> 00:16:28.640
for those early literacy skills.

00:16:28.640 --> 00:16:32.010
Most kids can read and they
don't need these foundational

00:16:32.010 --> 00:16:35.450
skills but dyslexic children
will not be able to do it

00:16:35.450 --> 00:16:37.790
without learning how
does reading work.

00:16:37.790 --> 00:16:41.020
And they try to trick you
because they're so smart

00:16:41.020 --> 00:16:43.630
and they depend upon
their visual memory.

00:16:43.630 --> 00:16:46.090
And finally, you know,
things fall apart

00:16:46.090 --> 00:16:49.760
by the time all this reading
to learn or when the text gets

00:16:49.760 --> 00:16:53.740
so complex, they can't
handle that, right?

00:16:53.740 --> 00:16:56.330
And so, as we look at that,
the other things, so they have

00:16:56.330 --> 00:16:58.170
that trouble with the
phonological component

00:16:58.170 --> 00:17:00.910
of the language, taking in those
sounds, putting those sounds

00:17:00.910 --> 00:17:04.370
to those symbols, but also, you
know, their spelling will be

00:17:04.370 --> 00:17:06.350
where you'll really,
really see it.

00:17:06.350 --> 00:17:10.560
Spanish speakers, you know,
the language is transparent

00:17:10.560 --> 00:17:13.470
and so you'll see that,
you know what, they're able

00:17:13.470 --> 00:17:16.530
to come along, it seems
like their decoding is OK,

00:17:16.530 --> 00:17:20.080
and where you'll find it is they
won't be very fluent readers

00:17:20.080 --> 00:17:23.350
and their spelling will
very clearly suffer.

00:17:23.350 --> 00:17:25.740
And so, what are the
secondary things that we see?

00:17:25.740 --> 00:17:29.730
Well, if I don't have access to
be able and the ability to be--

00:17:29.730 --> 00:17:32.020
you know, I need access
that you talk about.

00:17:32.020 --> 00:17:34.980
But now I can't read what's
in front of me and I want

00:17:34.980 --> 00:17:37.990
so desperately to be able
to do this and I'm smarter

00:17:37.990 --> 00:17:41.090
than this other kid that can
do it right next to me, right?

00:17:41.090 --> 00:17:43.290
And so what do we see
as secondary problems?

00:17:43.290 --> 00:17:45.340
Well, then you don't read.

00:17:45.340 --> 00:17:47.450
And because you don't
read, what will suffer?

00:17:47.450 --> 00:17:50.450
Your vocabulary will
suffer, you know.

00:17:50.450 --> 00:17:51.780
Your reading, you're
not going to read--

00:17:51.780 --> 00:17:53.770
if you can't read
accurately or fluently,

00:17:53.770 --> 00:17:57.030
eventually your reading
and comprehension is going

00:17:57.030 --> 00:18:00.910
to suffer, and then certainly
your written language.

00:18:00.910 --> 00:18:04.030
But the other thing is,
what are some early signs?

00:18:04.030 --> 00:18:07.260
And so-- I'm a speech and
language pathologist and so

00:18:07.260 --> 00:18:09.920
as I look at children,
when we see these children

00:18:09.920 --> 00:18:13.050
with these speech disorders
called phonological processing

00:18:13.050 --> 00:18:16.600
disorders, and we're trying to
really do the studies right now

00:18:16.600 --> 00:18:18.400
to really predict which ones

00:18:18.400 --> 00:18:22.490
of these phonological processing
disorders will have dyslexia

00:18:22.490 --> 00:18:23.790
and which ones won't.

00:18:23.790 --> 00:18:25.090
So that means these children--

00:18:25.090 --> 00:18:27.640
have you ever seen children
that when they speak to you,

00:18:27.640 --> 00:18:29.620
they're really little
toddlers, go-go-ga-ga.

00:18:29.620 --> 00:18:33.020
You don't understand
anything that they're saying.

00:18:33.020 --> 00:18:35.540
Well, we figure out in their
speech and language world

00:18:35.540 --> 00:18:39.460
that they have a phonological
processing disorder and we can,

00:18:39.460 --> 00:18:41.290
you know, really remediate that.

00:18:41.290 --> 00:18:43.280
We work with them intensely.

00:18:43.280 --> 00:18:46.780
But we follow those children
very carefully because many

00:18:46.780 --> 00:18:49.560
of them may also
have this disability

00:18:49.560 --> 00:18:52.130
that we know of as dyslexia.

00:18:52.130 --> 00:18:55.980
And the other thing is, you
know, dyslexia, this is a myth

00:18:55.980 --> 00:18:57.690
that it's a visual disorder.

00:18:57.690 --> 00:19:01.390
People think it's seeing things
backwards or mirror reading.

00:19:01.390 --> 00:19:03.570
In fact, you know, why
would they do that?

00:19:03.570 --> 00:19:07.350
Well, it's about disability
to sequence and the ability

00:19:07.350 --> 00:19:10.870
for directionality, knowing,
you know, that you do this first

00:19:10.870 --> 00:19:13.280
and next and left, my
right side, my left side.

00:19:13.280 --> 00:19:14.760
Some of us-- Actually
they've seen

00:19:14.760 --> 00:19:17.470
that some us women have
trouble with that too, right?

00:19:17.470 --> 00:19:19.340
But I know to ask
for directions.

00:19:19.340 --> 00:19:23.440
And the other thing is the
early things of just, you know,

00:19:23.440 --> 00:19:26.050
when we play with language,
you know, you all talk

00:19:26.050 --> 00:19:27.520
about Dr. Seuss books.

00:19:27.520 --> 00:19:30.580
You know, rhyming,
rhyming is so important.

00:19:30.580 --> 00:19:32.430
And these are things
that we've not only found

00:19:32.430 --> 00:19:35.170
out about the English
language, the Spanish language,

00:19:35.170 --> 00:19:37.860
alphabetic languages,
but we've also seen it

00:19:37.860 --> 00:19:41.600
in non-alphabetic languages
that how important this is.

00:19:41.600 --> 00:19:46.140
So this center-- this reading
center of the brain that we see

00:19:46.140 --> 00:19:50.160
in this left temporal lobe
is also your language center.

00:19:50.160 --> 00:19:53.260
And so I heard earlier
today mentioned about--

00:19:53.260 --> 00:19:56.190
you mentioned about listening
and speaking and reading

00:19:56.190 --> 00:19:58.460
and writing and being
a storyteller.

00:19:58.460 --> 00:20:01.860
But, you know, literacy
really, you know, we have--

00:20:01.860 --> 00:20:04.930
we must have these
opportunities for language

00:20:04.930 --> 00:20:06.750
to have ultimate
goal of literacy,

00:20:06.750 --> 00:20:10.890
and that ultimate goal is that
deep understanding of text

00:20:10.890 --> 00:20:13.940
and the enjoyment and
the ability to be engaged

00:20:13.940 --> 00:20:16.000
and motivated about it.

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:21.640
And so, because of these issues,
we start to feel really bad

00:20:21.640 --> 00:20:24.120
about ourselves if you
have these disabilities.

00:20:24.120 --> 00:20:26.360
And what will end up
happening for these students,

00:20:26.360 --> 00:20:30.220
if they don't have an expert
teacher that can help them

00:20:30.220 --> 00:20:32.750
and work through
these, what will end

00:20:32.750 --> 00:20:34.970
up happening is we
see high levels--

00:20:34.970 --> 00:20:36.580
you know, the National
Institute of Child Health

00:20:36.580 --> 00:20:39.720
and Human Development
sponsors our research.

00:20:39.720 --> 00:20:42.870
And they sponsor it because we
want to prevent these issues

00:20:42.870 --> 00:20:46.050
of reading disabilities but
also mental health disabilities.

00:20:46.050 --> 00:20:49.860
Because these individuals become
very anxious and depressed

00:20:49.860 --> 00:20:53.700
about there inability to
read, and when they know,

00:20:53.700 --> 00:20:58.350
I am just as smart as any-- this
person and anybody in this room.

00:20:58.350 --> 00:21:01.050
And so, we see these issues,

00:21:01.050 --> 00:21:02.980
issues also related
to attention.

00:21:02.980 --> 00:21:07.190
About 40% of our dyslexic
students will also have issues

00:21:07.190 --> 00:21:12.730
with attention, and so we
want to really get this early

00:21:12.730 --> 00:21:14.580
and remediate it early.

00:21:14.580 --> 00:21:19.650
And so, our mission now is--
and I've had the opportunity to,

00:21:19.650 --> 00:21:21.560
you know, really
understand about this.

00:21:21.560 --> 00:21:23.750
And through the National
Institute of Child Health

00:21:23.750 --> 00:21:28.410
and Human Development
grants and the Institute

00:21:28.410 --> 00:21:31.480
of Education Sciences at the
Department of Ed, we've been--

00:21:31.480 --> 00:21:34.960
you know, our research has
been funded and we've been able

00:21:34.960 --> 00:21:37.800
to look at these English
learners and we've been able

00:21:37.800 --> 00:21:40.920
to look at these children
with issues such as dyslexia,

00:21:40.920 --> 00:21:43.430
and we've been able to
look across languages

00:21:43.430 --> 00:21:45.970
and see what's going
on across languages.

00:21:45.970 --> 00:21:50.000
And finally, understanding
how beautiful it is

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:51.910
to be biliterate, to be--

00:21:51.910 --> 00:21:54.910
you know, to be able to
read across languages.

00:21:54.910 --> 00:21:57.490
But to know that
having that ability

00:21:57.490 --> 00:22:01.010
in one language will help
you in that second language.

00:22:01.010 --> 00:22:06.610
And so, we are looking now at
making sure that all children--

00:22:06.610 --> 00:22:08.850
so, our initiatives
now are to look

00:22:08.850 --> 00:22:12.020
in the general education
classrooms in these early years

00:22:12.020 --> 00:22:15.900
to make sure that children have
access to beautiful language,

00:22:15.900 --> 00:22:18.490
to understanding
how languages work,

00:22:18.490 --> 00:22:21.800
to understanding those
sound system, the phonology,

00:22:21.800 --> 00:22:25.160
understanding the morphology,
those words and word parts.

00:22:25.160 --> 00:22:27.880
Sixty percent of the English
language comes from Latin.

00:22:27.880 --> 00:22:29.670
And these, you know,
Latin and Greek roots

00:22:29.670 --> 00:22:33.350
which we call morphemes,
those are so important for us,

00:22:33.350 --> 00:22:36.040
for learning the vocabulary,
the second language.

00:22:36.040 --> 00:22:39.310
But also understanding
how it works and puts--

00:22:39.310 --> 00:22:41.990
how we put language
together for sentences,

00:22:41.990 --> 00:22:45.440
how sentences make paragraphs,
and how we're able to read.

00:22:45.440 --> 00:22:49.490
And so, just really looking at
that ability to get to what?

00:22:49.490 --> 00:22:50.790
What is our goal?

00:22:50.790 --> 00:22:53.990
To have a wonderful
comprehension

00:22:53.990 --> 00:22:56.930
and comprehension skills, but
first we have to make sure

00:22:56.930 --> 00:22:59.690
that they also have those
early literacy skills

00:22:59.690 --> 00:23:01.920
of being able to read.

00:23:01.920 --> 00:23:03.220
So, the--

