00:23:48.800 --> 00:23:52.710
&gt;&gt; Lydia Carlis: So,
I'm-- I am Lydia Carlis.

00:23:52.710 --> 00:23:58.870
And I am going to not talk
generally about people of color

00:23:58.870 --> 00:24:01.660
but specifically
about black children.

00:24:01.660 --> 00:24:08.030
And just say that a lot of
the same issues and concerns

00:24:08.030 --> 00:24:13.230
that Elsa just shared are
also issues and concerns

00:24:13.230 --> 00:24:17.160
for African-American
children learning English,

00:24:17.160 --> 00:24:22.330
learning this-- the language
of instruction and the language

00:24:22.330 --> 00:24:24.600
of business in schools.

00:24:24.600 --> 00:24:28.930
So, if African-American children
speak African-American English

00:24:28.930 --> 00:24:32.370
at home and they do not
learn how to code-switch,

00:24:32.370 --> 00:24:36.930
then they will be-- have
trouble reading later,

00:24:36.930 --> 00:24:42.480
they will have trouble
learning to read early.

00:24:42.480 --> 00:24:45.750
One of the statistics that I
read in my doctoral program

00:24:45.750 --> 00:24:49.120
that really solidified it for
me that I was going to work

00:24:49.120 --> 00:24:54.140
in early childhood was that
67% of children, who struggle

00:24:54.140 --> 00:24:56.990
to read in kindergarten,
continue to struggle

00:24:56.990 --> 00:24:58.800
to read in third grade.

00:24:58.800 --> 00:25:03.780
And so, while we have a country

00:25:03.780 --> 00:25:06.770
that does not have
universal preschool,

00:25:06.770 --> 00:25:09.200
that often does not
have mandatory

00:25:09.200 --> 00:25:13.370
or full-day kindergarten, we
know that there are so much

00:25:13.370 --> 00:25:15.330
that we can be doing
for children

00:25:15.330 --> 00:25:19.480
who struggle the most early,
and we should be doing that.

00:25:19.480 --> 00:25:23.950
And that is especially
important for children who need

00:25:23.950 --> 00:25:29.130
to learn both the language
of instruction and continue

00:25:29.130 --> 00:25:32.050
to value the language
that they speak at home,

00:25:32.050 --> 00:25:34.190
the dialect that
they speak at home.

00:25:34.190 --> 00:25:37.210
So, a lot-- there's
research coming out now

00:25:37.210 --> 00:25:42.790
that bidialectism is just as
been official as bilingualism.

00:25:42.790 --> 00:25:45.800
So, for your brain--
children who can do

00:25:45.800 --> 00:25:50.750
that code-switching
do have efficiency

00:25:50.750 --> 00:25:53.750
in both languages
is very important.

00:25:53.750 --> 00:25:57.260
So, this is something
to value and celebrate

00:25:57.260 --> 00:26:01.350
with African-American
children and not to talk

00:26:01.350 --> 00:26:04.230
about proper English
versus improper English,

00:26:04.230 --> 00:26:08.160
but talk about language of
school, language of instruction

00:26:08.160 --> 00:26:11.210
and your home language,
your home--

00:26:11.210 --> 00:26:14.240
like what you speak at
home is just as valuable.

00:26:14.240 --> 00:26:16.200
But we want to give
you opportunities

00:26:16.200 --> 00:26:20.120
and that's the same way that
we look at it with children

00:26:20.120 --> 00:26:22.090
who come to us speaking Spanish.

00:26:22.090 --> 00:26:24.800
But we don't always tell
African-American parents,

00:26:24.800 --> 00:26:28.140
please talk to your child
in your home dialect.

00:26:28.140 --> 00:26:30.690
I've never heard
teachers say that.

00:26:30.690 --> 00:26:33.570
But we will now, we
know what to say.

00:26:33.570 --> 00:26:36.610
