family doesn't have to pay,

00:40:24.430 --> 00:40:29.360
but you can order any book
and it is actually read

00:40:29.360 --> 00:40:33.200
by human being which
is very, very nice.

00:40:33.200 --> 00:40:37.960
The computer-generated speech
is getting much, much better

00:40:37.960 --> 00:40:39.670
but it's still
computer-generated.

00:40:39.670 --> 00:40:42.040
But these are actually
read by live people

00:40:42.040 --> 00:40:46.450
so you get the vocal inflection
and that kind of thing.

00:40:46.450 --> 00:40:51.390
And so, anyway, this is some
representative websites.

00:40:51.390 --> 00:40:56.830
But I would love to ask Elsa and
hear from others on my panel,

00:40:56.830 --> 00:41:01.330
what is the International
Dyslexia Association approach

00:41:01.330 --> 00:41:05.160
right now with people with
dyslexia specially children?

00:41:05.160 --> 00:41:10.830
How early should we introduce
audio books and, you know,

00:41:10.830 --> 00:41:14.290
make these tools available to
them versus continuing to try

00:41:14.290 --> 00:41:18.260
and help them and prioritize
them actually becoming readers?

00:41:18.260 --> 00:41:19.990
I think that's a
really huge issue.

00:41:19.990 --> 00:41:21.680
I'd love to hear your
perspective on that.

00:41:21.680 --> 00:41:22.980
&gt;&gt; Elsa Cardenas-Hagan: So yeah.

00:41:22.980 --> 00:41:27.280
So, well, the huge initiative
we have right now is making sure

00:41:27.280 --> 00:41:29.230
our teachers are well-equipped

00:41:29.230 --> 00:41:33.470
to teach all kids
including children

00:41:33.470 --> 00:41:35.800
with disabilities
such as dyslexia.

00:41:35.800 --> 00:41:39.020
And we can prevent many
of them ever getting

00:41:39.020 --> 00:41:42.020
to special education when we
do that before the third grade.

00:41:42.020 --> 00:41:43.810
I mean, we know that.

00:41:43.810 --> 00:41:46.910
And then when we don't identify
them before the third grade

00:41:46.910 --> 00:41:49.170
and we look at them at ninth
grade, we look at them at--

00:41:49.170 --> 00:41:50.890
there's-- they still remain--

00:41:50.890 --> 00:41:55.090
67% of them will remain
well below, you know,

00:41:55.090 --> 00:41:56.530
that expected reading level.

00:41:56.530 --> 00:41:58.850
So we're really focused
on, you know, more--

00:41:58.850 --> 00:42:00.590
you know, working
on the prevention

00:42:00.590 --> 00:42:04.570
as well as the intervention.

00:42:04.570 --> 00:42:05.870
But you-- [inaudible].

00:42:05.870 --> 00:42:07.170
What was that?

00:42:07.170 --> 00:42:08.850
So-- And by third, when we
look at them in third grade

00:42:08.850 --> 00:42:10.990
and we look at them
and we look--

00:42:10.990 --> 00:42:14.440
if we identify them in third
grade then we follow them

00:42:14.440 --> 00:42:16.550
to ninth grade, then
we're still seeing

00:42:16.550 --> 00:42:19.580
that they're still below
their average reading level

00:42:19.580 --> 00:42:20.880
in the ninth grade.

00:42:20.880 --> 00:42:22.180
&gt;&gt; They're below grade level.

00:42:22.180 --> 00:42:23.480
&gt;&gt; Elsa Cardenas-Hagan:
Yes, below grade level.

00:42:23.480 --> 00:42:25.430
&gt;&gt; And 50% of kids are
below grade level anyway.

00:42:25.430 --> 00:42:26.730
&gt;&gt; Elsa Cardenas-Hagan: Yeah.

00:42:26.730 --> 00:42:28.610
Yeah. You know, we
need to do a better--

00:42:28.610 --> 00:42:31.440
yeah, we have children
that aren't-- that's right.

00:42:31.440 --> 00:42:33.750
And especially when we look at
the English learners and we look

00:42:33.750 --> 00:42:35.600
at our African-American
population,

00:42:35.600 --> 00:42:38.070
if you look at the
NAEP scores, yes.

00:42:38.070 --> 00:42:41.310
But what we want to look at
in regards to that, you know,

00:42:41.310 --> 00:42:42.610
there's always the question

00:42:42.610 --> 00:42:46.700
about when do we introduce all
these extra accommodations,

00:42:46.700 --> 00:42:48.000
right?

00:42:48.000 --> 00:42:49.300
&gt;&gt; Laura Bailet: Right.

00:42:49.300 --> 00:42:50.600
&gt;&gt; Elsa Cardenas-Hagan:
Because then--

00:42:50.600 --> 00:42:51.900
you know, then you're like, oh
well, why should I have to read

00:42:51.900 --> 00:42:56.270
when I have all this
ability to gain the access.

00:42:56.270 --> 00:42:58.190
And then you're right
about young children.

00:42:58.190 --> 00:43:00.980
They're already, you know,
and as infants already--

00:43:00.980 --> 00:43:05.160
you see them already doing-- and
they have no fear of technology

00:43:05.160 --> 00:43:07.390
like us old people do.

00:43:07.390 --> 00:43:12.090
And so, you know, so,
number one, we always want

00:43:12.090 --> 00:43:15.260
to teach them to read but we do
also want them to have access

00:43:15.260 --> 00:43:20.740
and why can't you, you know,
do the both at the same time.

00:43:20.740 --> 00:43:23.470
&gt;&gt; Lydia Carlis: And I just say
for all kids, but especially

00:43:23.470 --> 00:43:28.760
for kids who are struggling
to read or to learn in school,

00:43:28.760 --> 00:43:30.060
teaching them

00:43:30.060 --> 00:43:33.740
about metacognition is super
important from preschool.

00:43:33.740 --> 00:43:37.530
So teaching them to understand
how they learn best is

00:43:37.530 --> 00:43:39.150
really important.

00:43:39.150 --> 00:43:40.450
Yeah.

00:43:40.450 --> 00:43:42.850
&gt;&gt; Laura Bailet: So I'd like
to open it up now to questions

00:43:42.850 --> 00:43:46.330
or comments from everyone in
the audience and also questions

00:43:46.330 --> 00:43:50.420
for the panel that went ahead
of us, creating, developing

00:43:50.420 --> 00:43:52.780
and sustaining lifelong readers.

00:43:52.780 --> 00:43:57.640
So, what do you guys think or
what questions do you have?

00:43:57.640 --> 00:43:59.230
&gt;&gt; Elsa Cardenas-Hagan: None.

00:43:59.230 --> 00:44:01.490
&gt;&gt; Lydia Carlis:
We answered it all.

00:44:01.490 --> 00:44:03.350
&gt;&gt; Elsa Cardenas-Hagan:
Can we ask a question?

00:44:03.350 --> 00:44:09.350
&gt;&gt; So I just have-- I'm just
kind of curious about folks

00:44:09.350 --> 00:44:14.530
that have dyslexia in
different orthographic system.

00:44:14.530 --> 00:44:16.060
So how does that play out?

00:44:16.060 --> 00:44:17.360
&gt;&gt; Elsa Cardenas-Hagan:
That's right.

00:44:17.360 --> 00:44:21.270
So, when we look across
languages, even languages

00:44:21.270 --> 00:44:26.010
that are non-alphabetic,
as I mentioned we do see

00:44:26.010 --> 00:44:29.580
that they still will have
difficulty in this issue,

00:44:29.580 --> 00:44:32.180
the phonological
component of the language.

00:44:32.180 --> 00:44:35.460
When we look at languages that
are more transparent such as

00:44:35.460 --> 00:44:40.450
like Italian and Spanish,
we see that, oh, you know,

00:44:40.450 --> 00:44:42.890
because of that transparency
and the regularity,

00:44:42.890 --> 00:44:44.320
they seem to be able to get

00:44:44.320 --> 00:44:47.570
at that decoding
OK, not so, so bad.

00:44:47.570 --> 00:44:50.040
But what they won't
have is the fluency

00:44:50.040 --> 00:44:53.870
and then the orthography,
the spelling and writing.

00:44:53.870 --> 00:44:57.470
&gt;&gt; Laura Bailet: There has been
a crosslinguistic research quite

00:44:57.470 --> 00:45:00.270
a bit and dyslexia has been
found in virtually every--

00:45:00.270 --> 00:45:01.850
in every written language, so.

00:45:01.850 --> 00:45:07.280
But the exact format and the
brain processing patterns

00:45:07.280 --> 00:45:11.640
associated with it will differ
according to the structure,

00:45:11.640 --> 00:45:13.720
the linguistic structure
of the language.

00:45:13.720 --> 00:45:15.090
So it's really fascinating.

00:45:15.090 --> 00:45:18.100
I mean, the-- You know, the
short answer is, as I said,

00:45:18.100 --> 00:45:21.280
learning to read is a
challenging task for the brain.

00:45:21.280 --> 00:45:23.760
I've heard one where a
scientist say, you know,

00:45:23.760 --> 00:45:25.180
dyslexia wasn't a problem

00:45:25.180 --> 00:45:29.090
until Gutenberg invented the
printing press in the 1400s

00:45:29.090 --> 00:45:32.160
and the masses were suddenly
expected to become readers.

00:45:32.160 --> 00:45:34.520
I mean, before then, you
know, it was a select few

00:45:34.520 --> 00:45:35.960
who were readers and writers--

00:45:35.960 --> 00:45:37.260
&gt;&gt; Elsa Cardenas-Hagan: Yeah.

00:45:37.260 --> 00:45:38.560
&gt;&gt; Laura Bailet: --
and everybody else,

00:45:38.560 --> 00:45:39.860
you know, was all oral.

00:45:39.860 --> 00:45:41.160
&gt;&gt; Elsa Cardenas-Hagan: Yeah.

00:45:41.160 --> 00:45:42.460
&gt;&gt; Laura Bailet: So all of a
sudden, we created a new class

00:45:42.460 --> 00:45:43.760
of disability with
the printing press.

00:45:43.760 --> 00:45:46.090
It's a very challenging
late-emerging skill

00:45:46.090 --> 00:45:47.930
in the course of
human development.

00:45:47.930 --> 00:45:52.750
So it is challenging that
having said that we do know how

00:45:52.750 --> 00:45:56.630
to teach most, if not
all children to read.

00:45:56.630 --> 00:45:59.500
And it is never too late
to teach someone to read,

00:45:59.500 --> 00:46:01.630
but you get far better outcomes

00:46:01.630 --> 00:46:05.010
if you take an earlier
preventive approach.

00:46:05.010 --> 00:46:06.680
So, was there a question--

00:46:06.680 --> 00:46:08.260
&gt;&gt; Elsa Cardenas-Hagan: So
I just have something more--

00:46:08.260 --> 00:46:09.560
&gt;&gt; Laura Bailet: OK.

00:46:09.560 --> 00:46:10.860
&gt;&gt; Elsa Cardenas-Hagan:
-- to mention about that.

00:46:10.860 --> 00:46:12.260
So in our-- our studies
are mainly

00:46:12.260 --> 00:46:15.890
with Spanish-speaking English
learners that have disabilities

00:46:15.890 --> 00:46:18.350
and then looking at those
components and looking

00:46:18.350 --> 00:46:21.450
across languages and
across linguistic features.

00:46:21.450 --> 00:46:25.580
And we find that, for example,
if they have those capabilities

00:46:25.580 --> 00:46:27.750
in their language, then
they're going to be

00:46:27.750 --> 00:46:29.760
on a great journey
towards literacy

00:46:29.760 --> 00:46:31.660
in their second language.

00:46:31.660 --> 00:46:33.820
And that if they didn't
have those abilities,

00:46:33.820 --> 00:46:36.240
then certainly it affects
their first language,

00:46:36.240 --> 00:46:39.910
it's going to certainly
affect their second language.

00:46:39.910 --> 00:46:44.110
&gt;&gt; Lydia Carlis: Benita,
do you have a question?

00:46:44.110 --> 00:46:45.410
&gt;&gt; Benita Somerfield: A lot

00:46:45.410 --> 00:46:47.830
of materials [inaudible]
disabilities.

00:46:47.830 --> 00:46:50.320
I mean, as you know,
as we've all said,

00:46:50.320 --> 00:46:53.610
the content of what people
read has a tremendous effect

00:46:53.610 --> 00:46:55.430
on motivation and
everything else.

00:46:55.430 --> 00:46:59.650
And as you mentioned, the
psychological damage to somebody

00:46:59.650 --> 00:47:02.810
with the child has
reading difficulties,

00:47:02.810 --> 00:47:06.870
learning difficulties only
increases as you go older.

00:47:06.870 --> 00:47:10.100
I've seen people say,
well, it's the same skills

00:47:10.100 --> 00:47:12.400
so we give them children's
materials--

00:47:12.400 --> 00:47:13.700
&gt;&gt; Laura Bailet: Right.

00:47:13.700 --> 00:47:15.000
&gt;&gt; Benita Somerfield:
That flies in the face

00:47:15.000 --> 00:47:16.440
of everything else that we know.

00:47:16.440 --> 00:47:18.300
Is there anything that
you would recommend

00:47:18.300 --> 00:47:21.260
that you've seen that's
specifically designed

00:47:21.260 --> 00:47:22.560
for adults?

00:47:22.560 --> 00:47:23.860
&gt;&gt; Laura Bailet: To
teach them reading

00:47:23.860 --> 00:47:27.400
but that's developmentally
appropriate teaching materials.

00:47:27.400 --> 00:47:28.700
&gt;&gt; Benita Somerfield:
Exactly, exactly.

00:47:28.700 --> 00:47:30.000
&gt;&gt; Laura Bailet: I think
that is a huge problem.

00:47:30.000 --> 00:47:32.410
And as much as there
are similarities

00:47:32.410 --> 00:47:36.130
in how children learn to read
and adults learn to read,

00:47:36.130 --> 00:47:38.500
they're very, very different.

00:47:38.500 --> 00:47:41.970
I really know what dyslexia
is, first and foremost,

00:47:41.970 --> 00:47:45.020
because I had to teach a
37-year-old dyslexic man

00:47:45.020 --> 00:47:46.320
to read.

00:47:46.320 --> 00:47:50.130
And I had previously been
trying to teach kindergarten

00:47:50.130 --> 00:47:52.110
through eight graders to read.

00:47:52.110 --> 00:47:54.710
And they-- But they weren't able

00:47:54.710 --> 00:47:56.710
to tell me what they
were getting

00:47:56.710 --> 00:47:58.080
and what they weren't getting.

00:47:58.080 --> 00:47:59.540
He was a really bright guy

00:47:59.540 --> 00:48:01.770
who had great self-awareness
and insight.

00:48:01.770 --> 00:48:05.600
He could tell me exactly
what parts made sense to him

00:48:05.600 --> 00:48:08.060
and exactly what didn't
make sense to him.

00:48:08.060 --> 00:48:09.790
And I feel like with
adult learners,

00:48:09.790 --> 00:48:14.830
we often don't take advantage
of the learning capabilities

00:48:14.830 --> 00:48:17.950
that they have that you
simply don't have at age six.

00:48:17.950 --> 00:48:21.510
But I don't know if you can
comment on specific programs.

00:48:21.510 --> 00:48:25.940
[ Inaudible ]

00:48:25.940 --> 00:48:27.240
&gt;&gt; Laura Bailet: Oh absolutely.

00:48:27.240 --> 00:48:29.430
&gt;&gt; Benita Somerfield:
Employees and everybody else.

00:48:29.430 --> 00:48:36.260
So their mental skills
extremely strong, quite bright.

00:48:36.260 --> 00:48:38.880
So not drawing on--
that's the major piece,

00:48:38.880 --> 00:48:41.620
not drawing on their
background information,

00:48:41.620 --> 00:48:43.640
not drawing on the
skills they've developed.

00:48:43.640 --> 00:48:47.910
They're pretending they are
the same as children by going

00:48:47.910 --> 00:48:52.360
through a skills-based approach
I think is, from my experience,

00:48:52.360 --> 00:48:53.770
is just a major mistake.

00:48:53.770 --> 00:48:58.250
&gt;&gt; Lydia Carlis: This is not
specific to adult with dyslexia

00:48:58.250 --> 00:49:02.280
but one of the amazing
interventions I saw

00:49:02.280 --> 00:49:08.880
at a Heard Start program
is that their approach

00:49:08.880 --> 00:49:13.580
to family literacy and how they
are teaching adult literacy is

00:49:13.580 --> 00:49:17.200
by using the child's
report card,

00:49:17.200 --> 00:49:22.090
by using the things they
go home, the newsletters

00:49:22.090 --> 00:49:24.290
so that they are
doing-- using something,

00:49:24.290 --> 00:49:28.290
materials that are important
to the parent and meaningful

00:49:28.290 --> 00:49:32.800
and they are going about that
in a way that it's systematic

00:49:32.800 --> 00:49:35.400
and supportive and helps
them get throughout the year

00:49:35.400 --> 00:49:36.700
and understanding they have

00:49:36.700 --> 00:49:38.330
to be great advocates
for their kids.

00:49:38.330 --> 00:49:40.000
&gt;&gt; Laura Bailet:
That gets back to,

00:49:40.000 --> 00:49:41.610
in a couple of the
earlier panels,

00:49:41.610 --> 00:49:45.390
the theme of relevance has kept
coming up, that the materials--

00:49:45.390 --> 00:49:47.070
you don't have to
have everything.

00:49:47.070 --> 00:49:49.480
It doesn't have to be
completely comprehensive.

00:49:49.480 --> 00:49:52.600
But whether you do have, it'd
better be relevant and it needs

00:49:52.600 --> 00:49:55.940
to be relevant like right
now because now they're going

00:49:55.940 --> 00:49:58.890
to read that report
card or that newsletter

00:49:58.890 --> 00:50:00.190
and they need to
respond right now.

00:50:00.190 --> 00:50:01.490
&gt;&gt; Lydia Carlis: Yeah.

00:50:01.490 --> 00:50:02.790
&gt;&gt; Laura Bailet: Two weeks

00:50:02.790 --> 00:50:04.090
from now they've
missed that opportunity.

00:50:04.090 --> 00:50:05.390
&gt;&gt; Lydia Carlis: Yeah.

00:50:05.390 --> 00:50:06.690
&gt;&gt; Laura Bailet: So
that just in time kind

00:50:06.690 --> 00:50:07.990
of relevance is important.

00:50:07.990 --> 00:50:09.290
Elsa, were you or--

00:50:09.290 --> 00:50:10.590
&gt;&gt; Elsa Cardenas-Hagan: Yeah.

00:50:10.590 --> 00:50:12.590
And I just think that that's
exactly what I was going to say.

00:50:12.590 --> 00:50:15.320
So you have to-- So when
you work with the adults,

00:50:15.320 --> 00:50:17.600
it has to be the things
that they want to read,

00:50:17.600 --> 00:50:21.510
what's relevant to them and
let's help you to figure out,

00:50:21.510 --> 00:50:25.270
you know, how to get through
that and understand it well.

00:50:25.270 --> 00:50:28.010
And so that's-- yeah,
you don't treat them

00:50:28.010 --> 00:50:29.380
like you would a little kid.

00:50:29.380 --> 00:50:30.680
Absolutely not.

00:50:30.680 --> 00:50:32.280
&gt;&gt; Laura Bailet: I can
share another quick story

00:50:32.280 --> 00:50:34.370
of my adult with dyslexia.

00:50:34.370 --> 00:50:36.910
So two things brought
him in to our clinic

00:50:36.910 --> 00:50:38.960
at Northwestern University.

00:50:38.960 --> 00:50:42.870
One was he want to be able
to read to his children,

00:50:42.870 --> 00:50:44.610
which he'd never done before.

00:50:44.610 --> 00:50:46.610
And number two, he
was so capable

00:50:46.610 --> 00:50:49.590
in his job at Glidden Paints.

00:50:49.590 --> 00:50:53.360
He was running all of their
very complicated equipment

00:50:53.360 --> 00:50:56.590
and machinery and he was
so good at it and this was

00:50:56.590 --> 00:51:01.110
in the late '70s, early '80s
when the EPA said, you know,

00:51:01.110 --> 00:51:04.060
we've got to stop, our
paint manufacturers have

00:51:04.060 --> 00:51:05.430
to stop polluting.

00:51:05.430 --> 00:51:08.230
And so, all the paint
manufacturers were going to have

00:51:08.230 --> 00:51:10.670
to spend millions and million
and millions of dollars

00:51:10.670 --> 00:51:13.970
on really expensive
anti-pollution equipment.

00:51:13.970 --> 00:51:18.450
So his boss had given him these
huge detailed manuals and said,

00:51:18.450 --> 00:51:21.710
Mel, I need you to read
this and tell us which piece

00:51:21.710 --> 00:51:23.540
of equipment we should buy.

00:51:23.540 --> 00:51:26.620
Well, you can imagine
his terror at that.

00:51:26.620 --> 00:51:29.050
He would take everything
home and his wife,

00:51:29.050 --> 00:51:32.600
who spoke like eight languages,
would read it aloud to him

00:51:32.600 --> 00:51:35.960
and he would memorize it,
that memory capability,

00:51:35.960 --> 00:51:38.340
so that he could go back
the next day and fake

00:51:38.340 --> 00:51:41.460
that he was reading it and
spelling off what it said.

00:51:41.460 --> 00:51:43.440
So those were the things
that brought him in,

00:51:43.440 --> 00:51:45.990
but what he really wanted to
do was open his own heating

00:51:45.990 --> 00:51:47.950
and refrigeration company.

00:51:47.950 --> 00:51:52.360
So I had to get him
through an 895-page textbook

00:51:52.360 --> 00:51:55.380
on heating and refrigeration.

00:51:55.380 --> 00:51:58.150
So that was quite a scene as
you can imagine for two years.

00:51:58.150 --> 00:52:04.040
I could never get him to see and
hear pattens and rhyming words

00:52:04.040 --> 00:52:06.610
like hat, mat, fat, cat, sat.

00:52:06.610 --> 00:52:10.290
But one day, one Tuesday night,
he brought the book into me

00:52:10.290 --> 00:52:14.660
and he was so excited to show me
he had highlighted all the words

00:52:14.660 --> 00:52:17.100
in this heating and
refrigeration book that ended

00:52:17.100 --> 00:52:23.000
in U-R-E, pressure,
moisture, temperature.

