01:04:18.220 --> 01:04:21.080
And like Meg said,
it's not just WNDB.

01:04:21.080 --> 01:04:22.790
It's all-- It's everybody.

01:04:22.790 --> 01:04:24.090
It's all of you.

01:04:24.090 --> 01:04:25.910
It's the librarians and the
teachers and the parents

01:04:25.910 --> 01:04:28.970
and booksellers and
everybody who cares.

01:04:28.970 --> 01:04:32.910
And that brings me to
the role of gatekeepers

01:04:32.910 --> 01:04:35.580
in children's literature,
because in general,

01:04:35.580 --> 01:04:39.800
we are talking about us as
gatekeepers who kind of all

01:04:39.800 --> 01:04:41.200
on the same page, right?

01:04:41.200 --> 01:04:45.140
That's what makes it-- If we're
here, we're probably all here.

01:04:45.140 --> 01:04:48.640
But we have to kind of take
this message more globally

01:04:48.640 --> 01:04:52.520
and make all people realize
how important it is to talk

01:04:52.520 --> 01:04:57.960
about like teaching empathy
to children from a young age,

01:04:57.960 --> 01:05:01.930
which I think if we take
the next slide-- no.

01:05:01.930 --> 01:05:04.600
OK. I'm skipping slides, sorry.

01:05:04.600 --> 01:05:06.570
I wanted to go to this slide.

01:05:06.570 --> 01:05:07.870
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: OK.

01:05:07.870 --> 01:05:10.790
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: Because
this was 2012, right?

01:05:10.790 --> 01:05:14.580
If we're talking about a
New York Times book list

01:05:14.580 --> 01:05:18.680
from that time period,
this is what the statistics

01:05:18.680 --> 01:05:19.980
for the books looked like.

01:05:19.980 --> 01:05:23.810
Out of 3600 books
published in that year,

01:05:23.810 --> 01:05:26.620
7% were about a child of color.

01:05:26.620 --> 01:05:29.690
And if we don't talk
to gatekeepers

01:05:29.690 --> 01:05:33.290
about why diversity is so
important, we're never going

01:05:33.290 --> 01:05:35.930
to change what's happening.

01:05:35.930 --> 01:05:37.400
We're always only
going to be talking

01:05:37.400 --> 01:05:40.060
to the same like-minded
people, right?

01:05:40.060 --> 01:05:41.710
We've got to kind of
get thee on that base

01:05:41.710 --> 01:05:43.210
so that we don't
have to go back.

01:05:43.210 --> 01:05:44.510
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich:

01:05:44.510 --> 01:05:46.560
And I think it has
a lot to do with--

01:05:46.560 --> 01:05:49.450
for ourselves, we should
start asking that question,

01:05:49.450 --> 01:05:53.110
as a writing assignment that's
given a lot, where I'm from

01:05:53.110 --> 01:05:55.030
or asking where am I from.

01:05:55.030 --> 01:05:59.030
So as gatekeepers asking
ourselves, even asking people

01:05:59.030 --> 01:06:01.320
who already feel like
we're doing pretty well

01:06:01.320 --> 01:06:07.660
or like we got this, where am
I from and what does that mean

01:06:07.660 --> 01:06:10.200
about the books that
I recommend,

01:06:10.200 --> 01:06:13.590
about how I share literature,
how I talk about literature,

01:06:13.590 --> 01:06:16.660
how I see the population
that I serve,

01:06:16.660 --> 01:06:20.430
am I sort of using
a deficit model.

01:06:20.430 --> 01:06:24.970
You can unconsciously-- What
are the implicit biases I have

01:06:24.970 --> 01:06:28.930
and asking ourselves those
hard questions and figuring

01:06:28.930 --> 01:06:33.190
out what we're going to do about
them on a very personal level.

01:06:33.190 --> 01:06:34.490
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: Yeah.

01:06:34.490 --> 01:06:35.790
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: Well, I'll tell
you one thing that changed

01:06:35.790 --> 01:06:38.070
for me in this whole process.

01:06:38.070 --> 01:06:40.970
So, I was a teacher
before I was an author.

01:06:40.970 --> 01:06:42.600
It was a job I loved.

01:06:42.600 --> 01:06:45.110
And of course, I loved--
the role of children's books

01:06:45.110 --> 01:06:47.250
in my classroom was
really, really large.

01:06:47.250 --> 01:06:51.840
As a teacher, I remember doing
this and certainly as an author.

01:06:51.840 --> 01:06:55.910
You know, and I was just talking
about this a few minutes ago

01:06:55.910 --> 01:06:57.620
because I have this book
coming out in September

01:06:57.620 --> 01:06:59.260
and you're waiting for
the reviews, right?

01:06:59.260 --> 01:07:01.530
And so, what are the
reviews you're thinking of?

01:07:01.530 --> 01:07:04.440
You're thinking of Kirkus, ah,
right, that's the scariest one

01:07:04.440 --> 01:07:06.070
of all, right, Kirkus review.

01:07:06.070 --> 01:07:10.230
And then SLJ and like all of
the major reviewing places.

01:07:10.230 --> 01:07:14.420
So the interesting thing
is that I have started

01:07:14.420 --> 01:07:19.900
to ask myself harder questions
about that relationship also

01:07:19.900 --> 01:07:23.610
because the truth is that those
reviewing agencies are also

01:07:23.610 --> 01:07:27.400
struggling with biases that
they're just now uncovering,

01:07:27.400 --> 01:07:32.550
and a lack of-- not a lack of,
but a very few number of people

01:07:32.550 --> 01:07:34.510
of color writing the reviews.

01:07:34.510 --> 01:07:37.930
And so, you don't know
what you don't know, right?

01:07:37.930 --> 01:07:46.430
You fall into these mistakes
or statements or lack of tuning

01:07:46.430 --> 01:07:49.600
into something really
important in the book

01:07:49.600 --> 01:07:51.870
because it's not part
of your experience.

01:07:51.870 --> 01:07:55.060
So, one thing that's really
changed for me is that sure,

01:07:55.060 --> 01:07:59.150
I go to Kirkus and SLJ
and so on and I'm picking

01:07:59.150 --> 01:08:01.860
out what they say
about my book and books

01:08:01.860 --> 01:08:07.370
that I'm interested in, but I
also make a stop at the blogs

01:08:07.370 --> 01:08:10.740
and so on of librarians
of color, of academics

01:08:10.740 --> 01:08:16.060
and I am trying to listen
to what the conversation is

01:08:16.060 --> 01:08:18.620
and to pick up on my own biases.

01:08:18.620 --> 01:08:21.460
And we were talking about
this at lunch that, you know,

01:08:21.460 --> 01:08:24.250
even with authors
of color and people

01:08:24.250 --> 01:08:26.790
from diverse backgrounds,
we have biases too.

01:08:26.790 --> 01:08:28.090
And it's so-- Like you have

01:08:28.090 --> 01:08:31.730
to just ask yourself
hard questions,

01:08:31.730 --> 01:08:34.080
which is I think
what we were talking

01:08:34.080 --> 01:08:39.020
about in terms of
this work at 2.0.

01:08:39.020 --> 01:08:43.950
It's now getting to the
really uncomfortable parts

01:08:43.950 --> 01:08:46.570
where you have to look
at things you used to do,

01:08:46.570 --> 01:08:49.190
opinions you've had,
and how you've changed

01:08:49.190 --> 01:08:50.720
and really owning them.

01:08:50.720 --> 01:08:52.020
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich: Yeah.

01:08:52.020 --> 01:08:54.170
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: I think it's also
important that we also talk

01:08:54.170 --> 01:08:58.100
about do we change, how we talk
about books in a way that like

01:08:58.100 --> 01:08:59.700
for example, for
me, I was always

01:08:59.700 --> 01:09:02.310
like representation is
important, you know,

01:09:02.310 --> 01:09:06.010
representation is
empowering, that's all great.

01:09:06.010 --> 01:09:08.290
And yes, absolutely,
very important.

01:09:08.290 --> 01:09:10.730
But empathy is really important.

01:09:10.730 --> 01:09:13.750
And part of that process is
making sure white kids read

01:09:13.750 --> 01:09:17.190
about black kids, black
kids read about Latino kids,

01:09:17.190 --> 01:09:19.320
Latino kids read
about Asian kids,

01:09:19.320 --> 01:09:20.620
Asian kids read about disabled.

01:09:20.620 --> 01:09:21.920
You see the circle?

01:09:21.920 --> 01:09:25.990
We have to actually be
completely open and learn

01:09:25.990 --> 01:09:29.030
from each other,
become empathetic.

01:09:29.030 --> 01:09:32.210
Empathy is not, you know,
something we're born with.

01:09:32.210 --> 01:09:33.970
Empathy is what we learn.

01:09:33.970 --> 01:09:37.480
If you don't know that
somebody from your--

01:09:37.480 --> 01:09:40.030
you know, from a different
community or background

01:09:40.030 --> 01:09:44.150
because you've never had any
experience with that, you know,

01:09:44.150 --> 01:09:46.340
community, where are
you going to turn to?

01:09:46.340 --> 01:09:47.640
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich:

01:09:47.640 --> 01:09:50.290
And I think that comes in I
think of how sometimes even

01:09:50.290 --> 01:09:54.410
when we mean well and mean to be
inclusive, we end up otherizing.

01:09:54.410 --> 01:09:59.070
And it reminds me one experience
I had as a middle schooler.

01:09:59.070 --> 01:10:03.100
After having been a kid
who moved around a lot

01:10:03.100 --> 01:10:04.720
to all these different
schools and different countries

01:10:04.720 --> 01:10:06.910
and being this new kid
like over and over,

01:10:06.910 --> 01:10:11.220
I came to this one school
in suburban New York

01:10:11.220 --> 01:10:14.300
where the teacher
meant to be welcoming.

01:10:14.300 --> 01:10:19.770
And my first day, when I
really just wanted to like stay

01:10:19.770 --> 01:10:22.780
under the radar, kind of
get the feel of the place

01:10:22.780 --> 01:10:26.970
and then be cool and fit in and
like, I don't know, be president

01:10:26.970 --> 01:10:31.210
or whatever I had in my head.

01:10:31.210 --> 01:10:33.310
I had just moved
from Lagos, Nigeria.

01:10:33.310 --> 01:10:34.810
We had lived in Lagos,
Nigeria for a year

01:10:34.810 --> 01:10:36.110
and then come to New York.

01:10:36.110 --> 01:10:38.260
So, the teacher was like, oh,

01:10:38.260 --> 01:10:41.290
we have a new student who's
just come to us from Africa.

01:10:41.290 --> 01:10:45.840
Come up to the front of the room
and tell us all about Africa.

01:10:45.840 --> 01:10:49.800
So, that was a problem for
a lot of different reasons.

01:10:49.800 --> 01:10:55.820
But the one thing that she did
was, in trying to, I think,

01:10:55.820 --> 01:10:59.060
include me and welcome me,
she really otherized me.

01:10:59.060 --> 01:11:02.950
And in middle school,
that's really like not cool.

01:11:02.950 --> 01:11:04.810
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: It's
where are you from?

01:11:04.810 --> 01:11:08.090
No, no, no, where
are you really from?

01:11:08.090 --> 01:11:12.370
And I now say my mother's
uterus, because like

01:11:12.370 --> 01:11:15.690
that is actually where
we're really from, you know.

01:11:15.690 --> 01:11:18.370
No, but seriously, the whole
point is that like this idea

01:11:18.370 --> 01:11:21.670
of like making feel--

01:11:21.670 --> 01:11:24.730
making people feel like they're
not real Americans is what comes

01:11:24.730 --> 01:11:26.030
from that question.

01:11:26.030 --> 01:11:30.270
So if we don't actually have
empathy and like from the start,

01:11:30.270 --> 01:11:33.660
making assumption that there's
no difference between us

01:11:33.660 --> 01:11:35.790
and that we can't
consider people

01:11:35.790 --> 01:11:40.620
from different backgrounds
as like, oh, I can't relate--

01:11:40.620 --> 01:11:42.620
which actually takes me to
another story by the way.

01:11:42.620 --> 01:11:44.130
I have to jump around.

01:11:44.130 --> 01:11:46.580
I tell the story a lot
because it's kind of important.

01:11:46.580 --> 01:11:48.280
I was once at the bookstore

01:11:48.280 --> 01:11:51.750
and there was a little
white girl reading

01:11:51.750 --> 01:11:53.140
"The Mighty Miss Malone"--

01:11:53.140 --> 01:11:54.440
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich: Oh, yeah.

01:11:54.440 --> 01:11:55.740
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: -- which
is a great book

01:11:55.740 --> 01:11:57.380
and has a little beautiful
little black girl on the cover.

01:11:57.380 --> 01:12:00.670
And this girl was like in--
She's reading this book.

01:12:00.670 --> 01:12:02.060
I mean, she's like
several chapters

01:12:02.060 --> 01:12:03.970
and she has broken the binding.

01:12:03.970 --> 01:12:05.900
I mean, I'm sitting
there thinking they need

01:12:05.900 --> 01:12:08.070
to buy this book, right?

01:12:08.070 --> 01:12:10.450
But then, her mother comes
over and takes the book

01:12:10.450 --> 01:12:13.080
out of her hand and says, no
honey, that book is not for you.

01:12:13.080 --> 01:12:14.380
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich: Yeah.

01:12:14.380 --> 01:12:15.680
That happens a lot.

01:12:15.680 --> 01:12:16.980
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: It happens a lot.

01:12:16.980 --> 01:12:18.280
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich: Yeah.

01:12:18.280 --> 01:12:19.580
I've had that so many times.

01:12:19.580 --> 01:12:20.880
Yeah.

01:12:20.880 --> 01:12:22.180
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: Yeah.

01:12:22.180 --> 01:12:23.480
So, what is the message
that that child took away?

01:12:23.480 --> 01:12:24.780
I'm not-- I don't
think that-- Sorry.

01:12:24.780 --> 01:12:26.610
I don't think that
the mom is racist,

01:12:26.610 --> 01:12:27.960
but I think her actions were.

01:12:27.960 --> 01:12:30.450
I think it was unintentional.

01:12:30.450 --> 01:12:31.750
And I think that's
what we have to talk

01:12:31.750 --> 01:12:35.660
about is systemic
racism, systemic bias

01:12:35.660 --> 01:12:38.630
that we've kind of-- the
biases that we've internalized

01:12:38.630 --> 01:12:41.180
without even knowing about it.

01:12:41.180 --> 01:12:42.740
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: I think
about that with the titles

01:12:42.740 --> 01:12:44.430
of my books sometimes.

01:12:44.430 --> 01:12:46.300
You know, I have Spanish
in the title a lot,

01:12:46.300 --> 01:12:48.910
"Tia Isa Wants a Car,"
"Mango, Abuela, and Me."

01:12:48.910 --> 01:12:50.960
So it's very identifiable,
right?

01:12:50.960 --> 01:12:53.390
You can pretty much
piece it together.

01:12:53.390 --> 01:13:01.970
And I have in my more insecure
moments wondered about someone

01:13:01.970 --> 01:13:05.040
like that standing in front of
the book and making a decision

01:13:05.040 --> 01:13:07.400
about who gets to
read this book.

01:13:07.400 --> 01:13:09.970
So-- And I think that
that's a real question.

01:13:09.970 --> 01:13:13.710
I mean, I've certainly met
librarians who will say,

01:13:13.710 --> 01:13:17.050
sometimes, we don't have very
many Latinos in my school

01:13:17.050 --> 01:13:19.830
so we don't really buy that
many books about Latinos.

01:13:19.830 --> 01:13:22.260
I've had, you know,

01:13:22.260 --> 01:13:25.170
conversations that
run like that.

01:13:25.170 --> 01:13:26.470
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: They
don't have any dragons

01:13:26.470 --> 01:13:27.770
in their neighborhood either.

01:13:27.770 --> 01:13:29.070
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: Right,
right, right.

01:13:29.070 --> 01:13:30.370
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: They
don't have any hobbits.

01:13:30.370 --> 01:13:31.670
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: Right.

01:13:31.670 --> 01:13:32.970
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: They don't
have any talking gorillas.

01:13:32.970 --> 01:13:34.270
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: They don't.

01:13:34.270 --> 01:13:35.570
They don't.

01:13:35.570 --> 01:13:36.870
But, you know, my feeling
is that if you don't,

01:13:36.870 --> 01:13:38.910
that's why you need my books
more than anybody else.

01:13:38.910 --> 01:13:40.210
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: Exactly.

01:13:40.210 --> 01:13:43.920
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: But I
do feel like that plays

01:13:43.920 --> 01:13:45.280
into just what you're saying.

01:13:45.280 --> 01:13:47.960
So, that's just an--
that's an example of--

01:13:47.960 --> 01:13:49.270
you know, like a simple bias

01:13:49.270 --> 01:13:52.330
that has really wide-reaching
repercussions.

01:13:52.330 --> 01:13:53.630
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: Exactly.

01:13:53.630 --> 01:13:54.930
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich:

01:13:54.930 --> 01:13:56.300
Or even in publishing, I've
had conversations with editors

01:13:56.300 --> 01:13:59.300
and agents who will
say, I really--

01:13:59.300 --> 01:14:01.810
I care about diverse literature.

01:14:01.810 --> 01:14:06.170
I want diverse authors
or diverse books,

01:14:06.170 --> 01:14:10.010
but they don't come across
my desk, or they don't come

01:14:10.010 --> 01:14:13.320
to me is basically the message.

01:14:13.320 --> 01:14:18.890
And the idea that, OK, maybe
you need to go out and look

01:14:18.890 --> 01:14:23.150
or do some extra work is
really difficult for a lot

01:14:23.150 --> 01:14:24.450
of people to understand.

01:14:24.450 --> 01:14:25.750
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: Yeah, yeah.

01:14:25.750 --> 01:14:27.810
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: Which takes me to
the next question, which I have

01:14:27.810 --> 01:14:31.720
to go back, right here.

01:14:31.720 --> 01:14:34.000
OK. So first of all, this
quote "We live in a world

01:14:34.000 --> 01:14:37.410
where the forces that seek
to divide us are strong.

01:14:37.410 --> 01:14:40.010
To overcome them, we must do
more than simply stand next

01:14:40.010 --> 01:14:41.680
to one another in silence."

01:14:41.680 --> 01:14:44.290
I love this quote
because it talks--

01:14:44.290 --> 01:14:47.430
to me, it takes us to
the point that right now,

01:14:47.430 --> 01:14:51.580
you're seeing the rise
of the author activist.

01:14:51.580 --> 01:14:53.340
So, I know why it's
important for me.

01:14:53.340 --> 01:14:57.630
I'd love Meg for you
to talk about it too.

01:14:57.630 --> 01:14:58.930
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: Well,
what I would say is

01:14:58.930 --> 01:15:04.130
that I don't have the luxury of
stepping out of who I am, right?

01:15:04.130 --> 01:15:10.040
So, a Latina woman, this is
the experience I have, and so,

01:15:10.040 --> 01:15:15.150
I don't feel like I can
turn my back on that.

01:15:15.150 --> 01:15:20.800
And I also feel like I just
can't see a way to do this work,

01:15:20.800 --> 01:15:24.780
publishing right now in this
time with this opportunity

01:15:24.780 --> 01:15:26.660
that is available to us

01:15:26.660 --> 01:15:30.610
to really reshape how we're
thinking about these books

01:15:30.610 --> 01:15:35.580
without doing some
heavy lifting.

01:15:35.580 --> 01:15:39.010
So, I have this thing
that I've been talking

01:15:39.010 --> 01:15:42.700
about called radical
abundance, right?

01:15:42.700 --> 01:15:44.600
Abundance is such a pretty word.

01:15:44.600 --> 01:15:46.200
It just sounds nice, right?

01:15:46.200 --> 01:15:48.760
And radical sort
of speaks to me.

01:15:48.760 --> 01:15:53.130
So, radical abundance
is my desire

01:15:53.130 --> 01:15:57.550
to certainly promote my own work
and my own creative development.

01:15:57.550 --> 01:15:59.140
That's great.

01:15:59.140 --> 01:16:04.690
But also, to make room at the
table for new authors who come.

01:16:04.690 --> 01:16:07.600
And the story that I often
use is my mother-in-law used

01:16:07.600 --> 01:16:11.430
to always say-- she had
this really ugly little--

01:16:11.430 --> 01:16:13.890
really ugly little
dining room table.

01:16:13.890 --> 01:16:16.900
It's a little round
thing, 42 inches.

01:16:16.900 --> 01:16:19.220
But the strangest thing
about this table is

01:16:19.220 --> 01:16:23.400
that if four people were sitting
there eating, we all fit.

01:16:23.400 --> 01:16:26.800
If six people were
eating, we still fit.

01:16:26.800 --> 01:16:29.630
If eight people were
eating, we were all there,

01:16:29.630 --> 01:16:31.210
cutting small, but
we were there.

01:16:31.210 --> 01:16:33.290
So, it's amazing, right?

01:16:33.290 --> 01:16:36.010
And she used to say, in Spanish,

01:16:36.010 --> 01:16:38.760
esta mesa se estira
como un chicle,

01:16:38.760 --> 01:16:42.560
meaning this table
stretches like a piece of gum.

01:16:42.560 --> 01:16:43.860
And I love that.

01:16:43.860 --> 01:16:46.540
And so, I feel like
it's important for us

01:16:46.540 --> 01:16:49.930
to stretch the table
like a piece of gum.

01:16:49.930 --> 01:16:54.900
So-- And it's easy,
it's fairly easy to do.

01:16:54.900 --> 01:17:00.790
So like when I'm invited to
NCTE to do a roundtable talk,

01:17:00.790 --> 01:17:05.650
my response is now, not
just, sure, I'd love to.

01:17:05.650 --> 01:17:10.450
My response is, I'd love to, do
you mind if I also bring Juana,

01:17:10.450 --> 01:17:14.070
so and so whose new book
is blah, blah, blah?

01:17:14.070 --> 01:17:17.610
If somebody is asking me to
blur books, I don't blur books,

01:17:17.610 --> 01:17:22.220
but I say I do other things,
can we do a shared thing

01:17:22.220 --> 01:17:24.210
on my blog or an event?

01:17:24.210 --> 01:17:28.430
So, that I'm introducing
somebody else.

01:17:28.430 --> 01:17:31.690
And I ask librarians and
teachers all the time

01:17:31.690 --> 01:17:36.500
to take a risk on new
authors coming to the table.

01:17:36.500 --> 01:17:39.070
You can invite the
six big Latino authors

01:17:39.070 --> 01:17:40.370
over and over again.

01:17:40.370 --> 01:17:41.850
We'd love to come.

01:17:41.850 --> 01:17:44.600
But there's more of us, right?

01:17:44.600 --> 01:17:48.680
So, pair us maybe, somebody
well-known with somebody new.

01:17:48.680 --> 01:17:51.550
And that's the radical
abundance.

01:17:51.550 --> 01:17:54.000
Now, the pushback that
I've gotten on it is this.

01:17:54.000 --> 01:17:58.020
From a very well-known author
who I respect immensely,

01:17:58.020 --> 01:18:00.240
she said to me, we're
at a conference,

01:18:00.240 --> 01:18:02.990
she said, but is that fair?

01:18:02.990 --> 01:18:07.550
She said, I have been at this
for 25 years and I was told,

01:18:07.550 --> 01:18:10.150
I'm sorry, I can't take
your book onto my list

01:18:10.150 --> 01:18:13.070
because we already
have an author

01:18:13.070 --> 01:18:15.920
of this background, et cetera.

01:18:15.920 --> 01:18:18.620
And, you know, she's
very accomplished now

01:18:18.620 --> 01:18:22.100
and she just feels like, is it
really fair to ask me after all

01:18:22.100 --> 01:18:24.150
of that work that I did to do--

01:18:24.150 --> 01:18:26.680
to keep doing this
now for you too?

01:18:26.680 --> 01:18:28.770
And I said it is not fair.

01:18:28.770 --> 01:18:33.020
But, you know, as my mother
always said, what ifs, right?

01:18:33.020 --> 01:18:38.280
And so, nothing is fair,
but that's the job, man.

01:18:38.280 --> 01:18:41.090
And so, that's what I say.

01:18:41.090 --> 01:18:46.610
So, I am encouraging you to
embrace radical abundance

01:18:46.610 --> 01:18:49.390
and to certainly don't
forget about my books.

01:18:49.390 --> 01:18:51.970
I really do want to come
to your schools and so on,

01:18:51.970 --> 01:18:55.180
but to take risks on new voices,

01:18:55.180 --> 01:18:59.490
and if I'm promoting a new
voice, to bother to pick

01:18:59.490 --> 01:19:02.380
up their book and see
what that's about.

01:19:02.380 --> 01:19:04.890
Because in the end,
like nobody is forever.

01:19:04.890 --> 01:19:06.190
You're not forever.

01:19:06.190 --> 01:19:07.490
You're not forever.

01:19:07.490 --> 01:19:08.790
I'm not forever.

01:19:08.790 --> 01:19:10.420
I'm going to have my day in the
sun and I'm thrilled for it,

01:19:10.420 --> 01:19:12.650
and it may be this day, right?

01:19:12.650 --> 01:19:14.690
But it's not forever.

01:19:14.690 --> 01:19:17.380
And it's important
to stretch the table.

01:19:17.380 --> 01:19:18.680
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich:

01:19:18.680 --> 01:19:20.590
What makes that uncomfortable?

01:19:20.590 --> 01:19:22.210
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: No, you can't just
say what Megs that [laughter].

01:19:22.210 --> 01:19:23.510
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich:

01:19:23.510 --> 01:19:24.810
What makes that--

01:19:24.810 --> 01:19:26.110
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: How do
you stretch the table?

01:19:26.110 --> 01:19:27.410
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich: I mean,

01:19:27.410 --> 01:19:29.100
I think it's stretching the
table and also all of us,

01:19:29.100 --> 01:19:31.610
like it doesn't have to just
be authors as activists,

01:19:31.610 --> 01:19:34.120
librarians as activists,
teachers as activists.

01:19:34.120 --> 01:19:39.460
Like all of us figuring out
in our space what we can do.

01:19:39.460 --> 01:19:42.350
And that really leads me to
talking about how sometimes

01:19:42.350 --> 01:19:47.270
that also leads to moments
or seasons of discomfort.

01:19:47.270 --> 01:19:48.570
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: Ah, wait, wait.

01:19:48.570 --> 01:19:50.390
Hold on. We have a
good one for this.

01:19:50.390 --> 01:19:52.920
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich: I do?

01:19:52.920 --> 01:19:55.820
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: Yes [laughter].

01:19:55.820 --> 01:19:57.780
I am uncomfortable.

01:19:57.780 --> 01:19:59.080
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich: Yeah.

01:19:59.080 --> 01:20:03.280
It does look terrible
[laughter], poor dog.

01:20:03.280 --> 01:20:05.660
But we-- I feel like we--

01:20:05.660 --> 01:20:09.060
so I mean, I do avoid
feeling uncomfortable

01:20:09.060 --> 01:20:10.800
and avoid discomfort.

01:20:10.800 --> 01:20:16.340
And as a-- When I first
started out as a literacy,

01:20:16.340 --> 01:20:18.430
whatever I was supposed to
be a literacy instructor,

01:20:18.430 --> 01:20:24.180
as a college freshman, I had
this experience of our job being

01:20:24.180 --> 01:20:28.070
to basically walk around these
neighborhoods in New York City

01:20:28.070 --> 01:20:32.500
and knock on people's door, it's
cold, and sort of be like, hey,

01:20:32.500 --> 01:20:35.970
I'm Olugbemisola and
I'm here to talk to you

01:20:35.970 --> 01:20:37.270
about nutrition and literacy.

01:20:37.270 --> 01:20:40.480
And it was this family
literacy program where we talked

01:20:40.480 --> 01:20:43.530
about recipes and
grocery shopping as a way

01:20:43.530 --> 01:20:46.270
to engage parents in
literacy activities

01:20:46.270 --> 01:20:48.620
and then we read to children.

01:20:48.620 --> 01:20:51.380
So, I had no idea
what I was doing.

01:20:51.380 --> 01:20:56.530
And I don't even know how we
got that job, like that day.

01:20:56.530 --> 01:21:01.070
But-- And we had a lot of
uncomfortable experiences

01:21:01.070 --> 01:21:03.740
and I had to work through them.

01:21:03.740 --> 01:21:08.420
I had an experience on my
very last day when I told one

01:21:08.420 --> 01:21:11.360
of the students in the
family that I would take her

01:21:11.360 --> 01:21:13.560
to the museum because she
had never been to the Museum

01:21:13.560 --> 01:21:14.860
of Natural History in New York.

01:21:14.860 --> 01:21:17.230
And so I was like, oh, I'll
take you to the museum.

01:21:17.230 --> 01:21:19.160
And her mom says that it was OK.

01:21:19.160 --> 01:21:23.400
I came to pick her up
on that day, I'm 18,

01:21:23.400 --> 01:21:26.040
and there were 17
other kids [laughter]

01:21:26.040 --> 01:21:29.390
who would come for
this museum trip.

01:21:29.390 --> 01:21:30.950
They had like called everybody.

01:21:30.950 --> 01:21:32.250
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: Field
trip [laughter].

01:21:32.250 --> 01:21:33.550
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich: Yes.

01:21:33.550 --> 01:21:34.850
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: Oh god.

01:21:34.850 --> 01:21:36.150
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich:

01:21:36.150 --> 01:21:37.450
I'm freaking out [laughter].

01:21:37.450 --> 01:21:38.750
What am I going to do?

01:21:38.750 --> 01:21:40.050
And so like we went to
the museum and luckily,

01:21:40.050 --> 01:21:42.100
the Natural History has
suggested admissions.

01:21:42.100 --> 01:21:44.210
So, I think I paid like
a dime for everybody.

01:21:44.210 --> 01:21:47.360
And then I had said we
would go to pizza afterward.

01:21:47.360 --> 01:21:51.140
And we went to this one place
that I didn't realize was

01:21:51.140 --> 01:21:53.150
like kind of high-end pizza.

01:21:53.150 --> 01:21:55.500
So, we went in and sat
down and drank our water.

01:21:55.500 --> 01:21:58.960
And then when I saw the menu, I
was like, guys, we have to get

01:21:58.960 --> 01:22:03.370
up and go because I
didn't have enough money.

01:22:03.370 --> 01:22:07.050
So, I say all this to
say that was discomfort.

01:22:07.050 --> 01:22:11.580
And sometimes when we don't
want to stretch ourselves

01:22:11.580 --> 01:22:14.340
or have these conversations,
we're thinking more

01:22:14.340 --> 01:22:19.020
about our own discomfort than
about our readers, our students,

01:22:19.020 --> 01:22:21.560
our-- the-- our communities
and our populations.

01:22:21.560 --> 01:22:24.700
And we're thinking
about not knowing--

01:22:24.700 --> 01:22:27.320
being afraid of being in
a position of not knowing

01:22:27.320 --> 01:22:32.770
or of losing authority
or of losing control.

01:22:32.770 --> 01:22:34.180
And I think we have
to understand

01:22:34.180 --> 01:22:38.270
that sometimes we're not going
to know and we're going to have

01:22:38.270 --> 01:22:41.130
to be in a position to tell
students or tell people,

01:22:41.130 --> 01:22:43.390
you know, I really don't know.

01:22:43.390 --> 01:22:46.620
Or think about doing
things a different way.

01:22:46.620 --> 01:22:49.680
I worked with a school that
had a book club for a long time

01:22:49.680 --> 01:22:54.260
that was a Newbery, sort
of Mock Newbery book club.

01:22:54.260 --> 01:22:58.730
Then one year, I did the
book club, but it was--

01:22:58.730 --> 01:23:01.760
we called it a Social
Justice Book Club.

01:23:01.760 --> 01:23:04.690
And what we did with
fifth graders was say, OK,

01:23:04.690 --> 01:23:06.170
you guys have a mission.

01:23:06.170 --> 01:23:07.820
There are a lot of
books in this library

01:23:07.820 --> 01:23:10.100
that nobody ever checks out.

01:23:10.100 --> 01:23:13.460
Let's go through and
analyze the shelves.

01:23:13.460 --> 01:23:15.780
First, let's think about
what we have in this library

01:23:15.780 --> 01:23:17.890
and why we think it's here.

01:23:17.890 --> 01:23:21.490
Is it because the adults love
these books when they were kids

01:23:21.490 --> 01:23:23.340
and just keep putting the
same books in the library?

01:23:23.340 --> 01:23:25.620
So, there was that issue that we
talked about with the students.

01:23:25.620 --> 01:23:31.220
And then, we pulled books
and said, OK, your mission is

01:23:31.220 --> 01:23:34.340
to read and share these
books with your peers.

01:23:34.340 --> 01:23:37.250
These are books that you
might think are great

01:23:37.250 --> 01:23:39.000
after you read them, but
nobody is reading them.

01:23:39.000 --> 01:23:42.900
So, how can we share these
books and get them circulating?

01:23:42.900 --> 01:23:45.300
So, the kids felt like
they had a mission

01:23:45.300 --> 01:23:47.990
and that they were
doing something

01:23:47.990 --> 01:23:50.710
to promote diverse books
in their community.

01:23:50.710 --> 01:23:52.630
And sometimes, we pulled books--

01:23:52.630 --> 01:23:54.990
the librarians and I pulled
books that all the kids

01:23:54.990 --> 01:23:57.890
in the club were like,
yeah, we don't like this.

01:23:57.890 --> 01:24:01.600
And we-- So, they
had space to say,

01:24:01.600 --> 01:24:04.100
we don't like this,
and here's why.

01:24:04.100 --> 01:24:05.450
You guys can try reading it.

01:24:05.450 --> 01:24:08.210
Good luck with that, but
this isn't our thing.

01:24:08.210 --> 01:24:11.180
And we just left that
space open to do that.

01:24:11.180 --> 01:24:12.480
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: Yeah.

01:24:12.480 --> 01:24:14.760
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: I think
the discomfort thing

01:24:14.760 --> 01:24:16.350
from the adult perspective
is this.

01:24:16.350 --> 01:24:19.550
I just had this talk at the
North Texas Teen Book Festival

01:24:19.550 --> 01:24:22.550
and that's that-- you're going
to-- you're in this room,

01:24:22.550 --> 01:24:26.610
we're all locked in this like
little suite bubble, right?

01:24:26.610 --> 01:24:29.100
This is not where the
heavy lifting happens.

01:24:29.100 --> 01:24:32.820
The heavy lifting happens
when you are at a meeting

01:24:32.820 --> 01:24:36.710
with someone who you admire
very much and you have to point

01:24:36.710 --> 01:24:41.580
out that a book on the shelf
is hurtful for x, y or z reason

01:24:41.580 --> 01:24:45.320
or you have to disagree about
the selection of the book

01:24:45.320 --> 01:24:47.600
or you have to point
out some bias.

01:24:47.600 --> 01:24:50.460
Like that's where
the heavy lifting is.

01:24:50.460 --> 01:24:53.340
Isn't it Neville who says
this in Harry Potter,

01:24:53.340 --> 01:24:55.920
he gets that award for
standing up to his friends

01:24:55.920 --> 01:24:57.880
in the first book
of Harry Potter?

01:24:57.880 --> 01:25:01.680
Like that's the award you
need to get people, right,

01:25:01.680 --> 01:25:04.620
because that's where the
heavy lifting is, right?

01:25:04.620 --> 01:25:07.160
That's where the discomfort is.

01:25:07.160 --> 01:25:10.610
The discomfort also comes for me

01:25:10.610 --> 01:25:14.110
when I'm asking myself harder
questions as I'm writing.

01:25:14.110 --> 01:25:15.410
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich: Yeah.

01:25:15.410 --> 01:25:17.150
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: So just
"Merci Suarez Changes Gears,"

01:25:17.150 --> 01:25:20.720
we were like in the late
stages, right, of pages.

01:25:20.720 --> 01:25:25.870
And, you know, I talk about
diversity all the time.

01:25:25.870 --> 01:25:27.460
Of course, I'm sensitive.

01:25:27.460 --> 01:25:31.430
Of course, I'm above making
any kind of mistake, blah.

01:25:31.430 --> 01:25:33.020
So, here's what happens, right?

01:25:33.020 --> 01:25:36.870
I'm reading through my pages,
looking for commas and so on,

01:25:36.870 --> 01:25:39.320
and I see this line
that Merci says.

01:25:39.320 --> 01:25:42.500
She's talking to her brother
and he's ignoring her.

01:25:42.500 --> 01:25:46.970
And she says, so Roli
plays death and what--

01:25:46.970 --> 01:25:49.320
you know, blah, blah,
blah, and it goes on.

01:25:49.320 --> 01:25:51.130
And I thought about that.

01:25:51.130 --> 01:25:53.900
I said, huh, well,
there's no problem saying

01:25:53.900 --> 01:25:57.050
that unless you are a
person who's hard of hearing

01:25:57.050 --> 01:25:58.500
or has hearing trouble.

01:25:58.500 --> 01:26:00.120
And then, it feels really lousy

01:26:00.120 --> 01:26:03.890
to have somebody
saying playing death.

01:26:03.890 --> 01:26:09.460
So, I struck it out and
I wrote something else.

01:26:09.460 --> 01:26:14.010
And I felt icky for being
a person who had made

01:26:14.010 --> 01:26:17.380
such a gross error, I guess.

01:26:17.380 --> 01:26:25.200
But I took the time to pause
and I ask myself hard questions.

01:26:25.200 --> 01:26:28.140
And the frustration
I have sometime is

01:26:28.140 --> 01:26:32.170
when authors don't take
that pause, and they assume

01:26:32.170 --> 01:26:35.080
that they have the
right tell any story

01:26:35.080 --> 01:26:41.190
and they don't necessarily
have the respect or the nuance

01:26:41.190 --> 01:26:43.860
or the understanding to tell it.

01:26:43.860 --> 01:26:45.160
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: Right.

01:26:45.160 --> 01:26:47.100
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: And then, they
hurt people and then you're

01:26:47.100 --> 01:26:50.270
in a position of
trying to explain why.

01:26:50.270 --> 01:26:52.950
That I find exhausting.

01:26:52.950 --> 01:26:54.250
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich: Yeah.

01:26:54.250 --> 01:26:55.550
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: Do you
find it exhausting?

01:26:55.550 --> 01:26:56.850
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich: Yeah.

01:26:56.850 --> 01:26:58.150
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: Oh yeah.

01:26:58.150 --> 01:26:59.450
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich: Yeah.

01:26:59.450 --> 01:27:00.750
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: We have
to be comfortable

01:27:00.750 --> 01:27:02.050
with being uncomfortable.

01:27:02.050 --> 01:27:03.350
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich: Yeah.

01:27:03.350 --> 01:27:04.650
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: Right?

01:27:04.650 --> 01:27:05.950
And I know that's hard.

01:27:05.950 --> 01:27:07.250
Nobody likes being
uncomfortable, right?

01:27:07.250 --> 01:27:08.550
It's like having a
perpetual wedgie.

01:27:08.550 --> 01:27:09.850
It's not comfortable [laughter].

01:27:09.850 --> 01:27:11.150
But--

01:27:11.150 --> 01:27:12.450
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: Like spanks.

01:27:12.450 --> 01:27:13.750
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: Yeah.

01:27:13.750 --> 01:27:15.050
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: Emotional spanks.

01:27:15.050 --> 01:27:16.350
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: Exactly.

01:27:16.350 --> 01:27:17.650
You just--

01:27:17.650 --> 01:27:18.950
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: Not that
we know [laughter].

01:27:18.950 --> 01:27:20.250
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: That's a
constipated look, Meg.

01:27:20.250 --> 01:27:21.550
Sorry.

01:27:21.550 --> 01:27:22.850
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: Yeah.

01:27:22.850 --> 01:27:24.150
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: Anyway.

01:27:24.150 --> 01:27:25.450
But for me, I think the
conversations are so important.

01:27:25.450 --> 01:27:26.750
And I'll just give
you an example.

01:27:26.750 --> 01:27:29.690
I was at an event and
somebody came to me

01:27:29.690 --> 01:27:33.950
and had taken screenshots of
my Facebook page at a time

01:27:33.950 --> 01:27:37.090
when I was very upset
about certain things

01:27:37.090 --> 01:27:39.340
that had politically
happened in the world

01:27:39.340 --> 01:27:41.490
and might have used
some language

01:27:41.490 --> 01:27:45.010
that might have been
very problematic.

01:27:45.010 --> 01:27:50.840
And so, they shared with me
my screenshots and told me

01:27:50.840 --> 01:27:53.540
that I was anti-white,

01:27:53.540 --> 01:27:58.870
that I was promoting white
genocide because, you know,

01:27:58.870 --> 01:28:00.170
talking about diversity

01:28:00.170 --> 01:28:02.940
in children's literature
promotes white genocide.

01:28:02.940 --> 01:28:05.530
I don't actually get
that connection myself.

01:28:05.530 --> 01:28:09.060
But this is the idealogy
that was coming at me.

01:28:09.060 --> 01:28:12.280
And if I had been 20 years
later, we would had a, you know,

01:28:12.280 --> 01:28:14.750
a showdown in the
parking lot, right?

01:28:14.750 --> 01:28:17.640
But age has mellowed me.

01:28:17.640 --> 01:28:20.130
And I was able to say
to her, you're right,

01:28:20.130 --> 01:28:22.030
I actually made a mistake.

01:28:22.030 --> 01:28:24.760
I shouldn't have used
such incendiary language.

01:28:24.760 --> 01:28:26.060
I wouldn't do it again.

01:28:26.060 --> 01:28:27.780
And then, I hope she
would actually sit

01:28:27.780 --> 01:28:32.010
down because she'd accused me
of having an LGBT agenda also.

01:28:32.010 --> 01:28:34.300
And I said, I hope she would
sit down and actually listen

01:28:34.300 --> 01:28:37.950
to my presentation and
talk to me about it.

01:28:37.950 --> 01:28:39.370
And she did.

01:28:39.370 --> 01:28:42.690
And this woman, who was so
angry and thought all these

01:28:42.690 --> 01:28:45.400
like horrible things about
diversity, actually came

01:28:45.400 --> 01:28:48.200
up to me after the presentation
and said, you're right,

01:28:48.200 --> 01:28:50.360
I see your point,
we do need diversity

01:28:50.360 --> 01:28:52.000
in children's literature.

01:28:52.000 --> 01:28:53.300
And she gave me a hug.

01:28:53.300 --> 01:28:56.070
So like, this was
a conversation.

01:28:56.070 --> 01:28:58.200
Of course, I was actually the
only one talking during the

01:28:58.200 --> 01:28:59.710
presentation, but she listened.

01:28:59.710 --> 01:29:01.010
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich:

01:29:01.010 --> 01:29:03.090
And that happened I think
because you were willing

01:29:03.090 --> 01:29:04.800
to say you're right,
I made a mistake.

01:29:04.800 --> 01:29:06.100
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: Exactly.

01:29:06.100 --> 01:29:07.400
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich:

01:29:07.400 --> 01:29:10.320
And it was so hard for us to say
I made a mistake or I'm sorry.

01:29:10.320 --> 01:29:14.140
And so just accept that
and acknowledge it rather

01:29:14.140 --> 01:29:18.340
than figure out ways to get
around it and justify it.

01:29:18.340 --> 01:29:19.640
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: Exactly.

01:29:19.640 --> 01:29:21.380
Yeah. I would also
like to get to a point

01:29:21.380 --> 01:29:24.640
where racism isn't a dirty word
and that people don't react

01:29:24.640 --> 01:29:27.360
to being called a racist
with that, you know,

01:29:27.360 --> 01:29:31.190
that like jerk reaction of
how dare you call me a racist.

01:29:31.190 --> 01:29:33.440
Like it's some kind of
fighting words kind of thing.

01:29:33.440 --> 01:29:36.170
And instead, why don't we
treat it like it's an illness?

01:29:36.170 --> 01:29:39.300
Why don't we treat it like
it is a disease that we,

01:29:39.300 --> 01:29:43.620
as a community, as a society,
have to work together to come

01:29:43.620 --> 01:29:46.810
up with a solution
and resolve it

01:29:46.810 --> 01:29:49.920
because it's systemic,
it's on everything.

01:29:49.920 --> 01:29:55.110
And if we don't actually work
together to address that issue,

01:29:55.110 --> 01:29:56.560
it's just going to continue.

01:29:56.560 --> 01:29:58.800
All we'll do is kind of
band-aid over the problem.

01:29:58.800 --> 01:30:00.330
What were you saying,
people will just try

01:30:00.330 --> 01:30:01.630
to game the system, you know?

01:30:01.630 --> 01:30:02.930
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich:

01:30:02.930 --> 01:30:04.230
Game the system.

01:30:04.230 --> 01:30:05.530
So, change the system.

01:30:05.530 --> 01:30:06.830
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: Exactly.

01:30:06.830 --> 01:30:08.130
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich: Yeah.

01:30:08.130 --> 01:30:09.430
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: Yeah.

01:30:09.430 --> 01:30:10.730
So, uncomfortable
conversations, like with--

01:30:10.730 --> 01:30:12.030
sometimes with family
too, right?

01:30:12.030 --> 01:30:14.200
So-- But what is next for us?

01:30:14.200 --> 01:30:15.800
Like what--

01:30:15.800 --> 01:30:17.100
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: Yeah.

01:30:17.100 --> 01:30:19.020
I-- You know, what would
3.0 look like, right?

01:30:19.020 --> 01:30:24.800
So, 2.0 looks like
to me advocacy

01:30:24.800 --> 01:30:26.850
and staying with the discomfort.

01:30:26.850 --> 01:30:31.060
And, you know, I have this
really superficial connection,

01:30:31.060 --> 01:30:33.030
which is I'm trying
to grow out my hair.

01:30:33.030 --> 01:30:34.650
OK. Let's just go to this.

01:30:34.650 --> 01:30:38.170
And my hairdresser, I sat
in the chair three days ago

01:30:38.170 --> 01:30:39.470
and I said, cut it all out.

01:30:39.470 --> 01:30:42.460
I wanted to cut again because
I can't stand this anymore.

01:30:42.460 --> 01:30:46.740
And she said to me as a good
hairdresser will, no, no.

01:30:46.740 --> 01:30:49.820
She said, I'm going to walk you
through this plateau [laughter].

01:30:49.820 --> 01:30:53.650
And I said, all right.

01:30:53.650 --> 01:30:56.030
And some of you are like,
we're talking about hair,

01:30:56.030 --> 01:30:58.400
how did we say like, you
know, but stay with me people.

01:30:58.400 --> 01:31:02.630
OK. So she said, no, no, we
will walk through this plateau.

01:31:02.630 --> 01:31:05.830
She said, I know it doesn't
feel like what you want to--

01:31:05.830 --> 01:31:07.380
et cetera, et cetera, et cetera.

01:31:07.380 --> 01:31:08.680
And this is just hair.

01:31:08.680 --> 01:31:09.980
It's the most superficial thing.

01:31:09.980 --> 01:31:11.280
But we're like in the plateau.

01:31:11.280 --> 01:31:14.620
So, we have to stay
together and walk

01:31:14.620 --> 01:31:18.120
through this uncomfortable
plateau, this ugly phase

01:31:18.120 --> 01:31:19.700
of being uncomfortable,

01:31:19.700 --> 01:31:22.750
of learning to have
delicate conversations

01:31:22.750 --> 01:31:26.970
and not deferring
always to being--

01:31:26.970 --> 01:31:29.400
no, I don't want to say
deferring to be polite

01:31:29.400 --> 01:31:31.350
because I do believe
in politeness.

01:31:31.350 --> 01:31:34.900
I do believe in offering
each other grace.

01:31:34.900 --> 01:31:38.550
I do believe in offering each
other respect always even

01:31:38.550 --> 01:31:41.210
when we're having
hard conversations.

01:31:41.210 --> 01:31:46.140
But don't defer to silence.

01:31:46.140 --> 01:31:47.440
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: Yes.

01:31:47.440 --> 01:31:48.740
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: Just standing
next to each other silently--

01:31:48.740 --> 01:31:50.040
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: Don't
be the bystander.

01:31:50.040 --> 01:31:52.250
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: -- and
thinking things without saying.

01:31:52.250 --> 01:31:54.580
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: I think the
bystander effect is something

01:31:54.580 --> 01:31:56.680
that we all have to
continue to recognize.

01:31:56.680 --> 01:32:02.380
Even I do it sometimes, right,
where you just feel too awkward

01:32:02.380 --> 01:32:05.860
and too uncomfortable
to confront a situation

01:32:05.860 --> 01:32:08.020
that you know is problematic.

01:32:08.020 --> 01:32:10.650
Sometimes, it's because it's
dangerous and you're scared,

01:32:10.650 --> 01:32:14.990
which actually self-preservation
is always first, of course.

01:32:14.990 --> 01:32:18.700
But if it's-- if there
is safety, I think it's--

01:32:18.700 --> 01:32:20.090
you know, we can't
be bystanders.

01:32:20.090 --> 01:32:22.030
We have to have the
conversation.

01:32:22.030 --> 01:32:26.130
We have to tell that racist
uncle that they're being racist,

01:32:26.130 --> 01:32:27.430
or you're mocker or something.

01:32:27.430 --> 01:32:28.730
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich:

01:32:28.730 --> 01:32:30.030
But even approaching--

01:32:30.030 --> 01:32:31.330
As a parent, sometimes
approaching schools

01:32:31.330 --> 01:32:33.980
about their book list
or their curricula.

01:32:33.980 --> 01:32:37.020
And one thing that I guess
3.0ish that we've seen is

01:32:37.020 --> 01:32:39.880
that schools have been
approaching WNDB and saying,

01:32:39.880 --> 01:32:42.310
we want to review-- do
a curriculum review.

01:32:42.310 --> 01:32:47.820
And there are books that we know
that our community holds dear

01:32:47.820 --> 01:32:53.120
that there are likely other
books that could replace them

01:32:53.120 --> 01:32:56.990
or be added to the curricula,
but we need to figure out how

01:32:56.990 --> 01:33:00.180
to have this conversation
with our community,

01:33:00.180 --> 01:33:01.780
but we're willing
to figure that out.

01:33:01.780 --> 01:33:04.390
We're willing to have
these conversations.

01:33:04.390 --> 01:33:05.690
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: Yeah.

01:33:05.690 --> 01:33:06.990
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich: We have--

01:33:06.990 --> 01:33:08.290
There's a book that
a lot of people love,

01:33:08.290 --> 01:33:11.170
that when I was a kid and read
it, I did not like at all,

01:33:11.170 --> 01:33:12.780
"To Kill a Mockingbird."

01:33:12.780 --> 01:33:15.550
And it was a book that I
had heard so much about

01:33:15.550 --> 01:33:18.070
and just was supposed
to be so great.

01:33:18.070 --> 01:33:19.890
And so when I read
it, I was furious

01:33:19.890 --> 01:33:21.930
because I did not
like it at all.

01:33:21.930 --> 01:33:24.650
And it's a lot of
peoples' favorites

01:33:24.650 --> 01:33:25.950
and on a lot of curricula.

01:33:25.950 --> 01:33:28.510
And for my daughter, when
it was on her curricula

01:33:28.510 --> 01:33:31.720
in the middle school, and when
she first got it, I was like,

01:33:31.720 --> 01:33:33.030
oh yeah, I hate that book.

01:33:33.030 --> 01:33:36.100
And we talked a little
bit about why,

01:33:36.100 --> 01:33:37.880
but I didn't really
talk too much about it

01:33:37.880 --> 01:33:40.110
because she was going
to read it herself.

01:33:40.110 --> 01:33:44.230
So, I wanted her to-- so she
came up feeling some type of way

01:33:44.230 --> 01:33:48.720
after she read it, and--
but was able to articulate

01:33:48.720 --> 01:33:51.650
that to her teacher
and in her classroom.

01:33:51.650 --> 01:33:56.070
And then, I guess, you know,
the school is kind of like

01:33:56.070 --> 01:33:58.890
where that come from, or
we're progressive school,

01:33:58.890 --> 01:34:02.710
we're already doing all
these wonderful things and--

01:34:02.710 --> 01:34:06.500
but was able to sort of
have this conversation

01:34:06.500 --> 01:34:10.230
within the discussion of
the book of who has power

01:34:10.230 --> 01:34:12.430
in the story, who has
agency in the story,

01:34:12.430 --> 01:34:14.180
what is-- what does this mean.

01:34:14.180 --> 01:34:17.080
So while the book as far
as I know is still part

01:34:17.080 --> 01:34:22.180
of that curriculum, at
least there's a willingness

01:34:22.180 --> 01:34:27.760
to discuss it and discuss
why and think about everyone

01:34:27.760 --> 01:34:30.940
in the community and how
these stories affect everyone,

01:34:30.940 --> 01:34:33.600
not just the people who
are like, this is classic

01:34:33.600 --> 01:34:36.280
and it's been here
and I love it.

01:34:36.280 --> 01:34:40.640
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: The Washington
Post just had a fantastic piece

01:34:40.640 --> 01:34:42.520
on "Challenging the Canon."

01:34:42.520 --> 01:34:44.110
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich: Yeah.

01:34:44.110 --> 01:34:45.830
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: So, I
encourage you to look that up.

01:34:45.830 --> 01:34:48.820
It was within a week
or two, I think.

01:34:48.820 --> 01:34:50.120
It was really wonderful.

01:34:50.120 --> 01:34:51.420
So the 3.0 thing I'd like to--

01:34:51.420 --> 01:34:52.720
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich:

01:34:52.720 --> 01:34:54.020
So schools are doing it.

01:34:54.020 --> 01:34:55.320
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: Oh, I'm sorry.

01:34:55.320 --> 01:34:56.620
The other 3.0 thing is
I'm always interested

01:34:56.620 --> 01:34:57.920
in who's still missing a table.

01:34:57.920 --> 01:35:00.130
And so within Latino
literature, I will tell,

01:35:00.130 --> 01:35:03.220
I would like to see more
authors from Honduras,

01:35:03.220 --> 01:35:05.460
from El Salvador,
from other countries.

01:35:05.460 --> 01:35:08.800
If you want to understand
this situation

01:35:08.800 --> 01:35:12.900
that we're facing right now with
immigration, with our borders

01:35:12.900 --> 01:35:17.250
and so on, you have to know that
history to see how we got here.

01:35:17.250 --> 01:35:21.760
We need more Afro-Latino
authors at the table.

01:35:21.760 --> 01:35:26.400
So, those are two areas that
I think within Latino kidlet,

01:35:26.400 --> 01:35:28.690
I'd like to see more
of in there.

01:35:28.690 --> 01:35:32.050
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: We definitely
need more native First Nations

01:35:32.050 --> 01:35:35.650
writers, indigenous writers
writing about their own cultures

01:35:35.650 --> 01:35:37.370
because their voice is missing.

01:35:37.370 --> 01:35:38.670
I mean, we have a few.

01:35:38.670 --> 01:35:39.970
We need more, right?

01:35:39.970 --> 01:35:41.270
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich:

01:35:41.270 --> 01:35:42.570
People with disabilities too.

01:35:42.570 --> 01:35:43.870
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: Yes.

01:35:43.870 --> 01:35:45.170
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich:

01:35:45.170 --> 01:35:46.470
The story of the people with
disabilities that are not--

01:35:46.470 --> 01:35:48.240
well, and all these cases
that are not problem stories,

01:35:48.240 --> 01:35:51.920
but stories about
people living rich

01:35:51.920 --> 01:35:53.220
and full lives in their own way.

01:35:53.220 --> 01:35:55.850
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: I mean, I
have two kids that suffer

01:35:55.850 --> 01:35:57.820
from crippling depression.

01:35:57.820 --> 01:35:59.930
And they are always looking
for the books that isn't

01:35:59.930 --> 01:36:02.360
about suicide or that
glamorizes suicide.

01:36:02.360 --> 01:36:04.020
What is with that, right?

01:36:04.020 --> 01:36:07.710
We need the books that show
them that it's OK, you can--

01:36:07.710 --> 01:36:10.170
you know, you can live

01:36:10.170 --> 01:36:14.300
and be successful even
with mental disease.

01:36:14.300 --> 01:36:16.010
We also need-- Like for me,

01:36:16.010 --> 01:36:20.500
Asian-American Pacific
Islander is this great big

01:36:20.500 --> 01:36:22.430
like amalgam, right?

01:36:22.430 --> 01:36:25.360
Let's talk about
how big that is.

01:36:25.360 --> 01:36:29.470
And we tend to focus on
East Asian writing the most,

01:36:29.470 --> 01:36:32.900
East and Southeast
Asian writers.

01:36:32.900 --> 01:36:35.290
We don't have enough
Pacific Islander, right,

01:36:35.290 --> 01:36:36.740
authors being published.

01:36:36.740 --> 01:36:38.650
We're not hearing their voice.

01:36:38.650 --> 01:36:39.950
So, I do think there's a lot

01:36:39.950 --> 01:36:41.900
of holes there that
we need to fill.

01:36:41.900 --> 01:36:45.460
But I think now, we
have time for questions

01:36:45.460 --> 01:36:48.130
because I see people
wanting to ask.

01:36:48.130 --> 01:36:50.720
So, can we now have questions?

01:36:50.720 --> 01:36:53.570
Yes? Would you like to ask?

01:36:53.570 --> 01:36:59.460
&gt;&gt; I just wanted to know
because you talked bout the way

01:36:59.460 --> 01:37:02.330
[inaudible] and someone spoke
to you about your Facebook post

01:37:02.330 --> 01:37:06.470
and then you spoke about
your daughter being able

01:37:06.470 --> 01:37:10.770
to articulate and have these
types of conversations,

01:37:10.770 --> 01:37:13.590
and I'm wondering how
do you teach people not

01:37:13.590 --> 01:37:17.760
to be bystanders and voice
their concerns articulately

01:37:17.760 --> 01:37:21.140
without being incendiary.

01:37:21.140 --> 01:37:27.690
And then also, how do you
speak so that people want

01:37:27.690 --> 01:37:31.620
to have understanding and
compassionate conversations

01:37:31.620 --> 01:37:34.750
because people do get on
the defense when you bring

01:37:34.750 --> 01:37:37.540
up racism or bias or bigotry.

01:37:37.540 --> 01:37:39.620
So, how do you have
compassionate,

01:37:39.620 --> 01:37:41.900
understanding conversations?

01:37:41.900 --> 01:37:44.530
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: So, you know
how like you have a--

01:37:44.530 --> 01:37:47.470
if you get an email and you
get really, really angry,

01:37:47.470 --> 01:37:50.140
you're at work, you got
an email, it makes you mad

01:37:50.140 --> 01:37:52.280
and it's probably your
boss and you get really mad

01:37:52.280 --> 01:37:54.320
and you start typing
a really angry email,

01:37:54.320 --> 01:37:58.560
but you don't hit send
because, self-preservation.

01:37:58.560 --> 01:38:01.110
You don't want to
get fired, right?

01:38:01.110 --> 01:38:03.240
That-- You know,
that split second

01:38:03.240 --> 01:38:08.140
where you recognize what you're
going to say is going to be bad,

01:38:08.140 --> 01:38:11.690
that's what saved me in
so many conversations,

01:38:11.690 --> 01:38:15.930
that I've had the ability
to stop, to bite my tongue,

01:38:15.930 --> 01:38:19.130
to push back the defensiveness
by the way, which usually

01:38:19.130 --> 01:38:24.470
that comes up, or the anger,
and then try to engage them

01:38:24.470 --> 01:38:27.820
in a conversation and
deflate their anger.

01:38:27.820 --> 01:38:29.120
So when-- like for example,

01:38:29.120 --> 01:38:32.740
when somebody is called a
racist, they get mad, right?

01:38:32.740 --> 01:38:36.590
How do you then address
the issue without getting

01:38:36.590 --> 01:38:40.060
that first gut reaction?

01:38:40.060 --> 01:38:43.920
For me, it's always been to
kind of like be the calmer one,

01:38:43.920 --> 01:38:47.800
but in kind and gentle and say,

01:38:47.800 --> 01:38:52.150
I understand why you're
upset by hearing this.

01:38:52.150 --> 01:38:54.510
Let's talk about those feelings.

01:38:54.510 --> 01:38:56.670
And I think that that's-- you
have to come with compassion

01:38:56.670 --> 01:38:58.450
because if you're just too
confident, they get mad

01:38:58.450 --> 01:38:59.750
because they're like, oh,

01:38:59.750 --> 01:39:01.050
you think you're
better than me, right?

01:39:01.050 --> 01:39:04.350
So, it's kind of like that,
you know, being compassionate

01:39:04.350 --> 01:39:07.960
and empathetic while trying to
have a difficult conversation.

01:39:07.960 --> 01:39:09.260
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich:

01:39:09.260 --> 01:39:10.560
And I think one thing--
like for my daughter,

01:39:10.560 --> 01:39:12.610
one thing that was--

01:39:12.610 --> 01:39:16.450
she's fortunate with is that
she has always had school

01:39:16.450 --> 01:39:21.990
experiences from the very
beginning where they--

01:39:21.990 --> 01:39:23.480
that kind of social-emotional
learning

01:39:23.480 --> 01:39:27.600
and those effective
communication lessons were

01:39:27.600 --> 01:39:30.080
always a part from kindergarten.

01:39:30.080 --> 01:39:33.560
And so, a resource that I
would recommend is the--

01:39:33.560 --> 01:39:35.750
I love the Morningside Center

01:39:35.750 --> 01:39:38.070
for teaching social
responsibility.

01:39:38.070 --> 01:39:39.500
And I use those.

01:39:39.500 --> 01:39:42.170
So the things that-- when I
used to work with first graders

01:39:42.170 --> 01:39:44.490
and second graders and
fifth graders on how

01:39:44.490 --> 01:39:47.750
to have these hard conversations
and talk in circles,

01:39:47.750 --> 01:39:49.570
or the things that sometimes
when my daughter was little

01:39:49.570 --> 01:39:52.410
and would come home and I would
kind of roll my eyes, like yeah,

01:39:52.410 --> 01:39:57.280
yeah, yeah, nobody really
talks like this, like OK, OK.

01:39:57.280 --> 01:40:01.460
But I see how they work and
I see how when children have

01:40:01.460 --> 01:40:05.660
that as part of their
education at school and--

01:40:05.660 --> 01:40:08.070
I mean, I'm fortunate that
I can reinforce it at home.

01:40:08.070 --> 01:40:11.940
But using those kind of lessons,
I use them all the time.

01:40:11.940 --> 01:40:15.520
When I-- Like the lessons
for elementary schoolers,

01:40:15.520 --> 01:40:18.190
I can go back and look at these
when I know that I'm going to be

01:40:18.190 --> 01:40:19.500
in a situation where
I might have

01:40:19.500 --> 01:40:22.560
to have a challenging
conversation.

01:40:22.560 --> 01:40:26.750
Literally go back and look at
those lessons for teachers or--

01:40:26.750 --> 01:40:30.160
of any age and think
about how I can apply them

01:40:30.160 --> 01:40:32.790
in the conversations
I'm going to have.

01:40:32.790 --> 01:40:34.850
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: I--
I'm going to just butt

01:40:34.850 --> 01:40:37.600
in because I'm remembering
Tim Tingle.

01:40:37.600 --> 01:40:41.090
We did one of our
first conferences here

01:40:41.090 --> 01:40:42.810
at the Library of Congress.

01:40:42.810 --> 01:40:46.350
It was talking about family
through the multicultural lens,

01:40:46.350 --> 01:40:51.390
like various people, how do
we see and write about family.

01:40:51.390 --> 01:40:53.420
And Ellen was on that panel,

01:40:53.420 --> 01:40:56.370
but so as Tim Tingle
who's a Choctaw author.

01:40:56.370 --> 01:41:00.950
And he said to a very
similar question,

01:41:00.950 --> 01:41:04.680
I remember that I am
meeting them on the bridge

01:41:04.680 --> 01:41:06.290
that they are crossing.

01:41:06.290 --> 01:41:07.610
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: Oh, yeah.

01:41:07.610 --> 01:41:08.910
That's right.

01:41:08.910 --> 01:41:13.670
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: And I
never forgot those words

01:41:13.670 --> 01:41:16.070
because when I'm
talking with someone

01:41:16.070 --> 01:41:20.620
who has a very deeply different
point of view or a point of view

01:41:20.620 --> 01:41:25.190
that I find hurtful or
just small in some way.

01:41:25.190 --> 01:41:30.660
I try to remember that
they're on a journey, right?

01:41:30.660 --> 01:41:35.380
And I'm going to try to be there
and help them cross that bridge.

01:41:35.380 --> 01:41:39.530
They won't all, and that's sad.

01:41:39.530 --> 01:41:41.240
But you know what,
it's also true,

01:41:41.240 --> 01:41:44.600
I'm on a journey crossing
a bridge for somebody else.

01:41:44.600 --> 01:41:47.310
There are going to be
moments that I make a mistake

01:41:47.310 --> 01:41:51.870
or I am not the most
empathetic and I hope

01:41:51.870 --> 01:41:54.220
that I'm greeted with grace.

01:41:55.250 --> 01:41:59.740
And I get a lot of stuff for
that, like for being too soft

01:41:59.740 --> 01:42:05.710
on people sometimes,
and I understand.

01:42:05.710 --> 01:42:10.960
But I think that if we allow the
conversation to just spiral up

01:42:10.960 --> 01:42:15.950
and get really terse,
we stop listening.

01:42:15.950 --> 01:42:18.290
It's like when my husband
and I fight, right?

01:42:18.290 --> 01:42:19.610
Like who's listening, right?

01:42:19.610 --> 01:42:20.910
So, like we got to calm.

01:42:20.910 --> 01:42:22.520
We got to go to the
ice cream parlor

01:42:22.520 --> 01:42:26.260
and share a hot fudge sundae or
something and then we can get

01:42:26.260 --> 01:42:27.560
to the bottom of things,

01:42:27.560 --> 01:42:30.820
which tells you how our
family runs [laughter].

01:42:30.820 --> 01:42:33.650
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: I also think
sometimes that you might feel

01:42:33.650 --> 01:42:36.090
like the conversation
is not going anywhere,

01:42:36.090 --> 01:42:37.390
but you never know.

01:42:37.390 --> 01:42:38.690
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: Yeah.

01:42:38.690 --> 01:42:40.500
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: You plant
those seeds wherever you can

01:42:40.500 --> 01:42:41.800
so that you're not
the bystander,

01:42:41.800 --> 01:42:44.740
that you have those
moments where you just kind

01:42:44.740 --> 01:42:46.780
of provide somebody with
a different perspective.

01:42:46.780 --> 01:42:50.970
And that maybe, that will become
a growing lesson for them.

01:42:50.970 --> 01:42:53.520
You won't see it, but maybe
somebody else will 10 years

01:42:53.520 --> 01:42:54.820
from now.

01:42:54.820 --> 01:42:56.120
&gt;&gt; Olugbemisola
Rhuday-Perkovich: Yeah.

01:42:56.120 --> 01:42:57.420
That happens a lot.

01:42:57.420 --> 01:42:58.720
&gt;&gt; Ellen Oh: Right, yeah.

